1
00:00:10,010 --> 00:00:12,511
[♪ 1920s jazz]

2
00:01:47,190 --> 00:01:49,691
[police siren in distance]

3
00:02:04,332 --> 00:02:05,833
[siren gets louder]

4
00:02:13,383 --> 00:02:15,259
[siren]

5
00:02:20,515 --> 00:02:22,057
[gunfire continues]

6
00:03:22,577 --> 00:03:24,369
[car horn]

7
00:03:29,292 --> 00:03:33,045
[♪ organ plays inside]

8
00:04:23,471 --> 00:04:25,472
All right, Charlie.

9
00:04:25,640 --> 00:04:28,016
- That the joint?
- Yes, sir.

10
00:04:28,184 --> 00:04:29,685
- Who runs it?
- I already told you.

11
00:04:29,852 --> 00:04:32,020
- Refresh my memory.
- Spats Colombo.

12
00:04:32,188 --> 00:04:35,190
- Very refreshing. What's the password?
- "I've come to Grandma's funeral."

13
00:04:35,358 --> 00:04:37,818
- Here's your admission card.
- Thanks, Charlie.

14
00:04:37,986 --> 00:04:40,404
If you want a ringside table,
just say you're a pallbearer.

15
00:04:40,571 --> 00:04:43,031
- OK, Charlie.
- We're all set. When's the kickoff?

16
00:04:43,199 --> 00:04:46,368
I'd better blow. If Colombo sees me,
it's goodbye, Charlie.

17
00:04:46,536 --> 00:04:47,869
Goodbye, Charlie.

18
00:04:50,540 --> 00:04:53,208
Give me five minutes,
then hit 'em with everything you got.

19
00:04:53,376 --> 00:04:55,043
You betcha.

20
00:05:10,727 --> 00:05:12,227
Good evening, sir.

21
00:05:12,395 --> 00:05:14,104
I'm Mr. Mozarella.
What can I do for you?

22
00:05:14,272 --> 00:05:15,689
I've come to the old lady's funeral.

23
00:05:15,857 --> 00:05:18,442
I haven't seen you
at our services before.

24
00:05:18,609 --> 00:05:20,944
- No, I've been on the wagon.
- Please.

25
00:05:21,112 --> 00:05:23,405
Where is the wake?
I'm one of the pallbearers.

26
00:05:23,573 --> 00:05:26,408
Show the gentleman into the chapel.
Pew number three.

27
00:05:26,576 --> 00:05:29,077
Yes, Mr. Mozarella. This way, sir.

28
00:05:31,664 --> 00:05:34,416
[♪ solemn organ music]

29
00:05:36,794 --> 00:05:40,714
[♪ jazz band plays
<i>Sweet Georgia Brown]</i>

30
00:05:47,347 --> 00:05:49,598
Well, if you gotta go,
that's the way to do it.

31
00:05:49,766 --> 00:05:51,266
Follow me, please.

32
00:06:04,906 --> 00:06:06,531
- What'll it be, sir?
- Booze.

33
00:06:06,699 --> 00:06:09,076
- Sorry. We only serve coffee.
- Coffee?

34
00:06:09,243 --> 00:06:12,037
Scotch coffee, Canadian coffee,
sour mash coffee...

35
00:06:12,205 --> 00:06:14,831
Scotch. Make it a demitasse,
with soda on the side.

36
00:06:14,999 --> 00:06:18,919
Wait a minute. Haven't you got
another pew not so close to the band?

37
00:06:19,087 --> 00:06:20,670
How about that one over there?

38
00:06:20,838 --> 00:06:24,132
Sorry, but that's reserved
for members of the immediate family.

39
00:06:34,685 --> 00:06:35,977
Oops!

40
00:06:42,276 --> 00:06:45,404
Hey! Hey, I want another cup of coffee.

41
00:06:45,571 --> 00:06:48,240
I want another cup of coffee.

42
00:06:59,335 --> 00:07:01,586
Better bring a check
in case the joint is raided.

43
00:07:01,754 --> 00:07:02,838
Who's gonna raid a funeral?

44
00:07:03,005 --> 00:07:05,715
Some people got no respect for the dead.

45
00:07:29,699 --> 00:07:32,159
Say, Joe. Tonight's the night, isn't it?

46
00:07:32,326 --> 00:07:35,495
- I'll say.
- No, tonight we get paid. That's good.

47
00:07:35,663 --> 00:07:38,957
- Why?
- I've got to see a dentist tomorrow.

48
00:07:39,125 --> 00:07:40,876
Dentist? We've been
out of work for four months,

49
00:07:41,043 --> 00:07:42,961
you wanna blow your first week's
pay on your teeth?

50
00:07:43,129 --> 00:07:44,880
Just a filling. Doesn't have to be gold.

51
00:07:45,047 --> 00:07:46,381
[mimics] "Doesn't have to be gold."

52
00:07:46,549 --> 00:07:48,884
How can you be so selfish? We owe rent.

53
00:07:49,051 --> 00:07:52,387
We owe $89 to Moe's Delicatessen.
Three Chinese lawyers are suing us

54
00:07:52,555 --> 00:07:53,972
because that check bounced
at the laundry.

55
00:07:54,140 --> 00:07:55,557
We borrowed money from
every girl in the line.

56
00:07:55,725 --> 00:07:57,392
- You're right.
- Of course I'm right.

57
00:07:57,560 --> 00:07:59,686
First thing tomorrow we'll pay
everyone something on account.

58
00:07:59,854 --> 00:08:01,146
- No, we don't. No.
- We don't?

59
00:08:01,314 --> 00:08:04,900
Tomorrow we go to the dog track
and bet it all on Greased Lightning.

60
00:08:05,067 --> 00:08:07,360
Greased Lightning?
You'd bet my money on a dog?

61
00:08:07,528 --> 00:08:10,864
He's a shoo-in. Max the waiter knows
the electrician that wires the rabbit.

62
00:08:11,032 --> 00:08:13,783
- What are you givin' me with a rabbit?
- The odds are 10 to 1.

63
00:08:13,951 --> 00:08:16,328
- Tomorrow we'll pay everybody.
- Suppose he loses.

64
00:08:16,496 --> 00:08:18,914
What are you worried about?
This job'll last a long time.

65
00:08:19,081 --> 00:08:23,460
- Suppose it doesn't.
- Jerry boy, why paint everything black?

66
00:08:23,628 --> 00:08:27,255
Suppose you got hit by a truck.
Suppose the stock market crashes.

67
00:08:27,423 --> 00:08:30,425
Suppose Mary Pickford
divorces Douglas Fairbanks.

68
00:08:30,593 --> 00:08:32,886
Suppose the Dodgers leave Brooklyn.

69
00:08:33,513 --> 00:08:35,722
- Joe?
- Suppose Lake Michigan overflows.

70
00:08:35,890 --> 00:08:39,100
Well, don't look now,
but the whole town is underwater.

71
00:08:43,689 --> 00:08:46,274
[rest of band plays on]

72
00:08:52,698 --> 00:08:53,990
Four,

73
00:08:54,158 --> 00:08:55,408
three,

74
00:08:55,576 --> 00:08:56,826
two,

75
00:08:56,994 --> 00:08:58,620
one.

76
00:09:00,248 --> 00:09:02,165
[police whistle]

77
00:09:02,333 --> 00:09:04,125
[gasps]

78
00:09:04,293 --> 00:09:06,044
[screaming]

79
00:09:07,838 --> 00:09:09,464
[whistle]

80
00:09:11,133 --> 00:09:14,636
All right, everybody. This is a raid.

81
00:09:14,804 --> 00:09:16,972
I'm a federal agent.
You're all under arrest.

82
00:09:18,599 --> 00:09:21,476
[drunken man]
I want another cup of coffee.

83
00:09:26,816 --> 00:09:28,608
[whistle]

84
00:09:33,447 --> 00:09:35,156
All right, Spats.

85
00:09:35,324 --> 00:09:37,993
- The services are over. Let's go.
- Go where?

86
00:09:38,160 --> 00:09:42,163
A country club for retired bootleggers.
I'm puttin' you up for membership.

87
00:09:42,331 --> 00:09:45,000
- I don't join nothin'.
- Oh, you'll like it there.

88
00:09:45,167 --> 00:09:48,920
I'll get the prison tailor to fit you
with a pair of special spats - striped.

89
00:09:50,256 --> 00:09:53,341
Big joke. What's the rap this time?

90
00:09:53,509 --> 00:09:57,220
Embalming people with coffee. 86 proof.

91
00:09:57,388 --> 00:09:59,806
Me? I'm just a customer.

92
00:09:59,974 --> 00:10:03,518
Oh, come on, Spats.
We know you own the joint.

93
00:10:03,686 --> 00:10:05,478
Mozarella's just frontin' for you.

94
00:10:05,646 --> 00:10:09,524
- Mozarella? Never heard of him.
- We got different information.

95
00:10:09,692 --> 00:10:12,527
From who? Toothpick Charlie maybe?

96
00:10:12,695 --> 00:10:15,905
Toothpick Charlie? Never heard of him.

97
00:10:17,783 --> 00:10:19,367
Buttermilk.

98
00:10:20,828 --> 00:10:23,204
Too smart to drink your own stuff, huh?

99
00:10:23,372 --> 00:10:26,416
Come on. On your feet.

100
00:10:26,584 --> 00:10:30,295
- You're wastin' the taxpayers' money.
- Call your lawyer if you wanna.

101
00:10:30,463 --> 00:10:34,341
These are my lawyers. All Harvard men.

102
00:10:35,509 --> 00:10:36,468
OK.

103
00:10:36,636 --> 00:10:44,267
I want another cup of coffee.

104
00:10:47,730 --> 00:10:49,522
- [police wagon bell]
- Get over there!

105
00:11:23,265 --> 00:11:26,768
That solves one problem. Now we don't
have to worry about who to pay first.

106
00:11:26,936 --> 00:11:29,604
- Quiet. I'm thinking.
- The landlady will lock us out.

107
00:11:29,772 --> 00:11:32,148
At Moe's Deli,
no more knockwurst on credit.

108
00:11:32,316 --> 00:11:34,609
We can't borrow from the girls -
they're on the way to jail.

109
00:11:34,777 --> 00:11:36,069
- Shut up.
- And we're...

110
00:11:36,237 --> 00:11:39,155
I wonder how much Sam the bookie
will give us for our overcoats.

111
00:11:39,323 --> 00:11:43,993
Sam the bookie? Nothin' doin'.
You're not puttin' my overcoat on a dog.

112
00:11:44,161 --> 00:11:46,996
- Jerry, I told you, it's a sure thing.
- We will freeze.

113
00:11:47,164 --> 00:11:49,582
It is below zero. We'll get pneumonia.

114
00:11:49,750 --> 00:11:53,628
Look, stupid, he's 10-1.
Tomorrow we'll have 20 overcoats.

115
00:11:53,796 --> 00:11:54,963
Joe...

116
00:11:56,382 --> 00:11:59,175
[wind howls]

117
00:12:04,348 --> 00:12:05,974
Greased Lightning.

118
00:12:06,142 --> 00:12:08,351
Why do I listen to you?
I oughta have my head examined.

119
00:12:08,519 --> 00:12:09,686
I thought you weren't talkin' to me.

120
00:12:09,854 --> 00:12:12,772
The bull fiddle's
dressed warmer than I am.

121
00:12:20,322 --> 00:12:21,614
- Anything today?
- Nothing.

122
00:12:21,782 --> 00:12:23,158
Thank you.

123
00:12:26,245 --> 00:12:27,996
- Anything today?
- Nothing.

124
00:12:28,164 --> 00:12:29,706
Thank you.

125
00:12:29,874 --> 00:12:31,416
I can't go on, Joe.

126
00:12:31,584 --> 00:12:34,335
I'm weak from hunger, I got a fever,
I got a hole in my shoe...

127
00:12:34,503 --> 00:12:37,297
If you gave me a chance,
we could be living like kings.

128
00:12:37,465 --> 00:12:39,174
- How?
- There's a dog running in the third.

129
00:12:39,341 --> 00:12:40,842
- His name is Galloping Ghost.
- Oh, no.

130
00:12:41,010 --> 00:12:44,471
Oh, yes. He's 15-1 and it's
his kind of a track. He's a real mudder.

131
00:12:44,638 --> 00:12:46,765
What do you want from me?
My head on a plate?

132
00:12:46,932 --> 00:12:49,601
No, just your bass. If we hock that
and my sax, we could get at least...

133
00:12:49,769 --> 00:12:53,396
Are you out of your mind? We're up the
creek and you wanna hock the paddle.

134
00:12:53,564 --> 00:12:56,816
All right, go ahead and starve.
What do I care? Freeze.

135
00:12:56,984 --> 00:12:59,611
- Anything today?
- Oh, it's you.

136
00:12:59,779 --> 00:13:01,529
Well, you've got a lot of nerve.

137
00:13:01,697 --> 00:13:03,031
Thank you.

138
00:13:03,991 --> 00:13:06,326
Joe. Come back here.

139
00:13:10,039 --> 00:13:13,541
Nellie, baby, if it's about Saturday
night, I can explain everything.

140
00:13:13,709 --> 00:13:17,337
What a heel. I spend $4
to get my hair marcelled,

141
00:13:17,505 --> 00:13:19,172
I buy me a brand-new negligee,

142
00:13:19,340 --> 00:13:21,716
I bake him a great big pizza pie.

143
00:13:21,884 --> 00:13:24,552
- And where were you?
- Where were you?

144
00:13:24,720 --> 00:13:26,054
- With you.
- Me?

145
00:13:26,222 --> 00:13:27,847
Don't you remember?
You had this bad tooth.

146
00:13:28,015 --> 00:13:30,058
It was impacted. His jaw was swoll out.

147
00:13:30,226 --> 00:13:31,267
It was?

148
00:13:31,435 --> 00:13:33,061
[muffled] Oh, yeah.

149
00:13:33,229 --> 00:13:35,730
Had to take him to the hospital,
give him a blood transfusion, right?

150
00:13:35,898 --> 00:13:37,232
Right. We have the same type blood.

151
00:13:37,399 --> 00:13:39,317
- Type O.
- Oh?

152
00:13:40,653 --> 00:13:42,195
Nellie, baby, I'll make it up to you.

153
00:13:42,363 --> 00:13:44,280
You're makin' it up
pretty good so far.

154
00:13:44,448 --> 00:13:47,909
As soon as we get a job, I'll take you
to the swellest restaurant in town.

155
00:13:48,494 --> 00:13:52,497
Oh... How about it? Has Poliakoff got
anything for us? We're desperate.

156
00:13:52,665 --> 00:13:56,668
Well, it just so happens
he is looking for a bass.

157
00:13:56,836 --> 00:13:58,586
And a sax.

158
00:13:58,754 --> 00:14:00,171
Right?

159
00:14:00,673 --> 00:14:02,048
Right.

160
00:14:02,216 --> 00:14:04,008
- What's the job?
- Three weeks in Florida.

161
00:14:04,176 --> 00:14:06,219
- Florida?
- At the Seminole-Ritz in Miami.

162
00:14:06,387 --> 00:14:08,930
Transportation and expenses all paid.

163
00:14:09,098 --> 00:14:11,975
Isn't she a bit of terrific?
Let's see Poliakoff.

164
00:14:12,142 --> 00:14:14,936
Hold on. He's got people with him.
You'll have to wait, boys.

165
00:14:15,104 --> 00:14:16,062
All right, we'll wait.

166
00:14:16,230 --> 00:14:18,565
Look, Gladys,
it's three weeks in Florida.

167
00:14:18,732 --> 00:14:21,317
Sweet Sue and Her Society Syncopators.

168
00:14:21,485 --> 00:14:24,279
They need a couple of girls
on sax and bass.

169
00:14:24,446 --> 00:14:28,116
Whaddaya mean, who is it?
It's Poliakoff. I got a job for ya.

170
00:14:28,576 --> 00:14:30,159
Gladys. Are ya there?

171
00:14:30,327 --> 00:14:31,953
Gladys!

172
00:14:32,705 --> 00:14:36,124
<i>Meshugeneh.</i>
Played 112 hours at a marathon dance.

173
00:14:36,292 --> 00:14:37,876
Now she's in bed
with nervous collapse.

174
00:14:38,043 --> 00:14:40,795
- Tell her to move over.
- What about Cora Jackson?

175
00:14:40,963 --> 00:14:44,299
Last I heard, she was playin'
with the Salvation Army.

176
00:14:44,466 --> 00:14:46,509
Drexel 9044.

177
00:14:46,677 --> 00:14:48,761
Oh, those idiot broads.

178
00:14:48,929 --> 00:14:52,974
Here we are, packed and ready to leave
for Miami, and what happens?

179
00:14:53,142 --> 00:14:58,229
The sax runs off with a Bible salesman
and the bass fiddle gets pregnant.

180
00:14:58,397 --> 00:15:00,356
Bienstock, I oughta fire you.

181
00:15:00,524 --> 00:15:03,818
Me? I'm the manager,
not the night watchman.

182
00:15:03,986 --> 00:15:06,571
Hello. Let me talk to Bessie Malone.

183
00:15:06,739 --> 00:15:09,324
What's she doing in Philadelphia?

184
00:15:09,491 --> 00:15:11,910
On the level?

185
00:15:12,077 --> 00:15:14,495
Bessie let her hair grow
and is playing with Stokowski.

186
00:15:14,663 --> 00:15:18,666
- Black Bottom Bessie?
- Schpielt zich mit der Philharmonic.

187
00:15:18,834 --> 00:15:20,793
How about Rosemary Schultz?

188
00:15:20,961 --> 00:15:22,754
Slashed her wrists when Valentino died.

189
00:15:22,922 --> 00:15:26,466
We might as well all slash our wrists
unless we round up two dames by tonight.

190
00:15:26,634 --> 00:15:29,052
You know the kind of girls we need.
We don't care where you find them.

191
00:15:29,219 --> 00:15:31,012
Just get them on
that train by 8 o'clock.

192
00:15:31,180 --> 00:15:32,889
[speaks foreign language]

193
00:15:33,057 --> 00:15:35,266
The moment anything turns up,
I'll give you a tinkle.

194
00:15:35,434 --> 00:15:38,186
Bye, Sig. I wonder
if I've got room for another ulcer.

195
00:15:38,354 --> 00:15:40,688
Nellie, get me long-distance.

196
00:15:40,856 --> 00:15:42,815
- Look, Sig, we wanna talk to you.
- What is it?

197
00:15:42,983 --> 00:15:45,360
- About the Florida job.
- The Florida job?

198
00:15:45,527 --> 00:15:47,612
- Nellie told us about it.
- We're not too late, are we?

199
00:15:47,780 --> 00:15:50,281
What are ya? Couple of comedians?
Get out of here.

200
00:15:50,449 --> 00:15:52,992
Long distance? Get me the
William Morris Agency in New York.

201
00:15:53,160 --> 00:15:54,702
You need a bass and a sax, don't you?

202
00:15:54,870 --> 00:15:56,704
The instruments are right
but you're not.

203
00:15:56,872 --> 00:15:58,373
I wanna speak to Mr. Morris.

204
00:15:58,540 --> 00:16:01,584
- Wait, what's wrong with us?
- You're the wrong shape. Goodbye.

205
00:16:01,752 --> 00:16:03,962
Wrong shape? What are you looking for?
Hunchbacks or something?

206
00:16:04,129 --> 00:16:07,048
- It's not the backs that worry me.
- What kind of a band is it?

207
00:16:07,216 --> 00:16:09,384
- You gotta be under 25.
- We could pass for that.

208
00:16:09,551 --> 00:16:11,094
- Gotta be blond.
- We could dye our hair.

209
00:16:11,261 --> 00:16:12,345
And you gotta be girls.

210
00:16:12,513 --> 00:16:14,263
- We could...
- No, we couldn't.

211
00:16:14,431 --> 00:16:17,058
- Mr. William Morris.
- You mean this is a girls' band?

212
00:16:17,226 --> 00:16:19,686
Yeah, that's what he means. Good
old Nellie. I could wring her neck.

213
00:16:19,853 --> 00:16:20,853
I'm holding on.

214
00:16:21,021 --> 00:16:23,481
Let's talk this over.
Why couldn't we do it?

215
00:16:23,649 --> 00:16:26,609
Last year when we worked in the
gypsy tearoom, we wore gold earrings.

216
00:16:26,777 --> 00:16:29,570
Remember when you booked us with
the Hawaiian band, we wore grass skirts.

217
00:16:30,406 --> 00:16:33,741
- What's with him? He drinks?
- No, he ain't eatin' so good.

218
00:16:33,909 --> 00:16:35,576
Got an empty stomach
and it's gone to his head.

219
00:16:35,744 --> 00:16:37,912
Joe, this is three weeks in Florida.

220
00:16:38,080 --> 00:16:39,914
We could borrow clothes
from the chorus girls.

221
00:16:40,082 --> 00:16:41,916
- You've flipped your wig.
- Now you're talking.

222
00:16:42,084 --> 00:16:46,045
Now he is talking! We get
second-hand wigs, a little padding.

223
00:16:46,213 --> 00:16:48,840
We call ourselves
Josephine and Geraldine.

224
00:16:49,008 --> 00:16:51,926
- Josephine and Geraldine... Come on.
- Yeah.

225
00:16:52,094 --> 00:16:55,013
Look, if you wanna pick up
a little money tonight,

226
00:16:55,180 --> 00:16:59,183
at the University of Illinois
they're havin' a St. Valentine's dance.

227
00:16:59,351 --> 00:17:01,728
- We'll take it.
- You got it. $6 a man.

228
00:17:01,895 --> 00:17:03,771
Be on the campus
at Urbana at 8 o'clock.

229
00:17:03,939 --> 00:17:06,649
All the way to Urbana
for a one-night stand?

230
00:17:06,817 --> 00:17:09,819
It's $12. We can get
one of the overcoats out of hock.

231
00:17:09,987 --> 00:17:13,072
Hello. Mr. Morris?
This is Poliakoff in Chicago.

232
00:17:13,240 --> 00:17:16,701
You wouldn't happen to have a couple
of girl musicians available, would you?

233
00:17:16,869 --> 00:17:18,244
A sax player and a bass?

234
00:17:18,412 --> 00:17:20,038
Look, if William Morris
doesn't come through...

235
00:17:20,205 --> 00:17:22,457
Come on, Geraldine.

236
00:17:24,084 --> 00:17:27,420
It's 100 miles. It's snowin' outside.
How do we get there?

237
00:17:27,588 --> 00:17:29,130
- I'll think of something.
- Like what?

238
00:17:29,298 --> 00:17:31,674
- Don't crowd me.
- "Don't crowd me..."

239
00:17:31,842 --> 00:17:35,470
- How'd it go, girls?
- Ooh, you! I oughta wring your neck.

240
00:17:35,637 --> 00:17:38,264
Please, Jerry. That's no way to talk.

241
00:17:39,183 --> 00:17:41,225
Nellie baby, what are you doin' tonight?

242
00:17:41,393 --> 00:17:45,438
- Tonight? Why?
- 'Cause I've got some plans.

243
00:17:45,606 --> 00:17:49,067
- I'm not doing anything.
- Really?

244
00:17:49,234 --> 00:17:53,112
I just thought I'd go home
and have some cold pizza.

245
00:17:53,280 --> 00:17:55,031
Then you'll be in all evening?

246
00:17:55,574 --> 00:17:57,075
Yes, Joe.

247
00:17:57,242 --> 00:17:59,243
Good. Then you won't
be needing your car.

248
00:17:59,411 --> 00:18:02,413
My car? Why, you...

249
00:18:04,291 --> 00:18:07,418
Isn't he a bit of terrific?

250
00:18:09,838 --> 00:18:10,797
[wind howls]

251
00:18:16,386 --> 00:18:19,514
We coulda had three weeks
in Florida, all expenses paid.

252
00:18:19,681 --> 00:18:22,934
Lyin' in the sun,
palm trees, flyin' fish...

253
00:18:23,102 --> 00:18:24,519
Knock it off, will ya?

254
00:18:27,856 --> 00:18:31,526
Possible straight, possible nothing,
and a pair of eights.

255
00:18:34,530 --> 00:18:36,531
All right, drop 'em, you guys.

256
00:18:36,698 --> 00:18:38,991
- Drop what?
- We came for a car.

257
00:18:39,159 --> 00:18:41,744
- Oh, yeah?
- Yeah. Nellie Weinmeyer's car.

258
00:18:45,707 --> 00:18:46,666
Musicians.

259
00:18:46,834 --> 00:18:48,376
Wise guys.

260
00:18:48,544 --> 00:18:50,920
OK, let's go. Aces bet.

261
00:18:51,088 --> 00:18:54,006
It's a '25 Hupmobile,
green, coupe... sir.

262
00:18:54,174 --> 00:18:56,425
- It's over here.
- [Jerry] Yeah, over here.

263
00:18:56,593 --> 00:19:01,556
- Want some gas?
- Yeah, about 40 cents' worth, please.

264
00:19:01,723 --> 00:19:04,892
- Put it on Miss Weinmeyer's bill?
- Uh... Yeah. Why not?

265
00:19:05,060 --> 00:19:07,019
And while you're at it, fill it up.

266
00:19:07,563 --> 00:19:09,689
[tires screech]

267
00:19:17,030 --> 00:19:19,740
All right, everybody. Hands up.

268
00:19:22,244 --> 00:19:23,953
Face the wall.

269
00:19:26,748 --> 00:19:28,332
You too, Toothpick.

270
00:19:28,625 --> 00:19:33,796
Come on.

271
00:19:45,225 --> 00:19:48,436
Hey. Join us.

272
00:19:59,948 --> 00:20:01,657
OK, boss.

273
00:20:14,463 --> 00:20:17,256
Hello, Charlie. Long time no see.

274
00:20:17,424 --> 00:20:19,550
What is it, Spats?
What are you doin' here?

275
00:20:19,718 --> 00:20:21,636
[Spats]
I just dropped in to pay my respects.

276
00:20:21,803 --> 00:20:23,971
- You don't owe me nothin'.
- I wouldn't say that.

277
00:20:24,139 --> 00:20:26,641
You were nice enough to recommend
my mortuary to your friends.

278
00:20:26,808 --> 00:20:28,142
I don't know what you're talkin' about.

279
00:20:28,310 --> 00:20:30,311
Now I got all
those coffins on my hands.

280
00:20:30,479 --> 00:20:33,981
- And I hate to see 'em go to waste.
- I had nothin' to do with it.

281
00:20:34,149 --> 00:20:37,902
Oh, too bad, Charlie.
You woulda had three eights.

282
00:20:42,157 --> 00:20:45,117
- Goodbye, Charlie.
- No, Spats, no.

283
00:20:45,285 --> 00:20:46,869
No, Spats. Please, no.

284
00:20:53,377 --> 00:20:54,835
I think I'm gonna be sick.

285
00:20:55,003 --> 00:20:56,629
[liquid gushes]

286
00:21:01,510 --> 00:21:03,678
All right, come on outta there.

287
00:21:04,304 --> 00:21:08,349
Come on.

288
00:21:08,517 --> 00:21:13,145
- We didn't see anything. Did we?
- What? No. Not a thing.

289
00:21:13,313 --> 00:21:16,524
Besides, it's none of our business
if you guys wanna bump each other off.

290
00:21:18,151 --> 00:21:21,529
Say... Don't I know you two
from somewhere?

291
00:21:21,697 --> 00:21:24,323
Oh, no. We're just
a couple of musicians.

292
00:21:24,491 --> 00:21:27,201
We came to pick up a car.
Nellie Weinmeyer's car.

293
00:21:27,369 --> 00:21:29,370
There's a dance tonight.

294
00:21:29,538 --> 00:21:31,872
- Come on, Jerry.
- Wait a minute.

295
00:21:32,040 --> 00:21:33,207
Where do you think you're goin'?

296
00:21:33,375 --> 00:21:36,627
Urbana. It's about
100 miles from here, so don't...

297
00:21:36,795 --> 00:21:38,879
You're not goin' nowhere.

298
00:21:41,049 --> 00:21:43,884
- We're not?
- [Spats] I don't like no witnesses.

299
00:21:44,052 --> 00:21:47,388
- [Joe] We won't breathe a word.
- You won't breathe nothin'.

300
00:21:47,556 --> 00:21:49,682
Not even air.

301
00:22:20,088 --> 00:22:22,089
[police siren]

302
00:22:22,257 --> 00:22:25,634
All right, boys, let's blow out of here.
We'll take care of those guys later.

303
00:22:40,609 --> 00:22:42,610
I think they got me.
I think they got me.

304
00:22:42,778 --> 00:22:44,945
- They got the bull fiddle.
- No blood?

305
00:22:45,113 --> 00:22:48,157
If they catch us, there'll be blood
all over. Type O. Come on.

306
00:22:48,325 --> 00:22:50,785
[sirens]

307
00:22:52,829 --> 00:22:54,663
[horn honking]

308
00:23:01,963 --> 00:23:04,298
- Where are you running?
- As far away as possible.

309
00:23:04,466 --> 00:23:09,261
It's not far enough. Those guys know us.
Every hood in Chicago will be after us.

310
00:23:13,308 --> 00:23:15,434
[sirens continue blaring]

311
00:23:22,526 --> 00:23:23,651
- Quick, gimme a nickel.
- What?

312
00:23:23,819 --> 00:23:25,986
- Gimme a nickel.
- All right.

313
00:23:27,948 --> 00:23:29,031
You're gonna call the police?

314
00:23:29,199 --> 00:23:31,617
Police? We'd never live to testify
against Spats Colombo.

315
00:23:31,785 --> 00:23:32,952
Wabash 1098.

316
00:23:33,120 --> 00:23:35,371
Joe, we gotta get out of town.
Maybe we should grow beards.

317
00:23:35,539 --> 00:23:37,331
We are getting out of town,
but we're gonna shave.

318
00:23:37,499 --> 00:23:38,416
- Shave?
- Shave.

319
00:23:38,583 --> 00:23:42,128
At a time like this? They wanna blast
our heads off, and you wanna shave.

320
00:23:42,295 --> 00:23:44,755
- Shave our legs, stupid.
- Shave our legs...?

321
00:23:46,675 --> 00:23:49,051
[high-pitched voice]
Hello. Mr. Poliakoff?

322
00:23:49,219 --> 00:23:52,513
I understand you're looking
for a couple of girl musicians.

323
00:23:53,306 --> 00:23:56,267
Mm-hm... Mm-hm...

324
00:23:56,435 --> 00:23:58,519
- Mm-hm...
- Mm-hm...

325
00:24:10,115 --> 00:24:13,534
<i>[man over PA] Florida Limited leaving</i>
<i>on track one for Washington,</i>

326
00:24:13,702 --> 00:24:17,371
<i>Charleston, Savannah,</i>
<i>Jacksonville and Miami.</i>

327
00:24:17,539 --> 00:24:20,374
<i>All aboard. All aboard.</i>

328
00:24:26,047 --> 00:24:27,047
Ow!

329
00:24:28,467 --> 00:24:29,383
What's the matter now?

330
00:24:29,551 --> 00:24:32,386
How do they walk in these things?
How do they keep their balance?

331
00:24:32,554 --> 00:24:35,222
Must be the way the weight
is distributed. Now come on.

332
00:24:36,433 --> 00:24:38,976
It is so drafty.

333
00:24:39,144 --> 00:24:40,853
They must catch cold all the time.

334
00:24:41,021 --> 00:24:43,898
- Quit stalling. We'll miss the train.
- I feel naked.

335
00:24:44,065 --> 00:24:46,901
- I feel like everybody's starin' at me.
- With those legs? Are you crazy?

336
00:24:47,068 --> 00:24:48,360
Now, come on.

337
00:24:51,198 --> 00:24:52,239
Uh-oh.

338
00:24:58,205 --> 00:25:00,539
It's no use. We're not gonna
get away with it, Joe.

339
00:25:00,707 --> 00:25:03,876
My name is Josephine, and this was
your idea in the first place.

340
00:25:27,609 --> 00:25:30,986
Look at that. Look how she moves.

341
00:25:31,154 --> 00:25:33,739
That's just like JELL-O on springs.

342
00:25:33,907 --> 00:25:36,784
They must have some sort of
built-in motor or something.

343
00:25:37,285 --> 00:25:39,662
I tell ya, it's a whole different sex.

344
00:25:39,829 --> 00:25:42,456
What are you afraid of?
Nobody's asking you to have a baby.

345
00:25:42,624 --> 00:25:43,832
This is just to get us out of town.

346
00:25:44,000 --> 00:25:45,709
Once we get to Florida,
we'll blow this whole setup.

347
00:25:45,877 --> 00:25:48,295
Joe, this time, I am not gonna
let you talk me into something...

348
00:25:48,463 --> 00:25:51,549
Extra. Extra. Seven slaughtered
in North Side garage.

349
00:25:51,716 --> 00:25:54,176
Fear of bloody aftermath. Extra. Extra.

350
00:25:54,344 --> 00:25:57,930
- You talked me into it. Let's go.
- Attagirl, Geraldine.

351
00:26:00,600 --> 00:26:01,850
- Rosella.
- Fiddle.

352
00:26:02,018 --> 00:26:03,769
- Move along, Dolores.
- Trombone.

353
00:26:03,937 --> 00:26:05,980
- Hey, Olga, how's your back?
- Trumpet.

354
00:26:08,692 --> 00:26:12,236
- Uh... Well, here we are.
- Are you two from the Poliakoff Agency?

355
00:26:12,404 --> 00:26:14,655
- Yes. We're the new girls.
- Brand new.

356
00:26:14,823 --> 00:26:17,408
- This is our manager, Mr. Bienstock.
- How do you do?

357
00:26:17,576 --> 00:26:19,493
And I'm Sweet Sue.

358
00:26:19,661 --> 00:26:21,996
My name is Josephine.

359
00:26:22,163 --> 00:26:23,747
- I'm Daphne.
- Hm?

360
00:26:24,958 --> 00:26:28,335
Saxophone, bass. Am I glad to see
you girls. You saved our lives.

361
00:26:28,503 --> 00:26:30,462
[Josephine] Likewise, I'm sure.

362
00:26:30,630 --> 00:26:32,756
Where did you girls play before?

363
00:26:32,924 --> 00:26:36,176
Here, there and... around, and...

364
00:26:36,344 --> 00:26:40,306
We spent three years
at the Sheboygan Conservatory of Music.

365
00:26:41,057 --> 00:26:42,516
[conductor] All aboard.

366
00:26:42,684 --> 00:26:44,810
You're in berths 7 and 7A.

367
00:26:44,978 --> 00:26:46,186
7 and 7A.

368
00:26:46,354 --> 00:26:48,188
- Thanks ever so.
- You're welcome.

369
00:26:48,356 --> 00:26:49,732
Oh! The feeling's mutual.

370
00:26:51,860 --> 00:26:54,862
- Upsy-daisy.
- Fresh.

371
00:26:55,030 --> 00:26:57,573
Looks like Poliakoff came through
with a couple of real ladies.

372
00:26:57,741 --> 00:27:00,034
You'd better tell the other girls
to watch their language.

373
00:27:00,201 --> 00:27:02,369
[train whistle]

374
00:27:10,920 --> 00:27:12,087
What are you...?

375
00:27:12,255 --> 00:27:13,797
[whispers] Daphne?

376
00:27:13,965 --> 00:27:16,842
I never did like the name Geraldine.

377
00:27:23,725 --> 00:27:27,186
Hi. I'm the bass fiddle.
Just call me Daphne.

378
00:27:27,354 --> 00:27:28,395
[all] Hi!

379
00:27:28,563 --> 00:27:30,898
My name is Josephine. Sax.

380
00:27:31,066 --> 00:27:32,232
[all] Hi!

381
00:27:32,400 --> 00:27:35,903
- Welcome to No Man's Land.
- [all] You'll be sorry.

382
00:27:36,071 --> 00:27:39,406
- Take off your corsets and spread out.
- Oh, I don't wear one myself.

383
00:27:39,574 --> 00:27:41,992
- Don't you bulge?
- Huh? Bulge? Me?

384
00:27:42,160 --> 00:27:45,371
I have the most divine seamstress.
Comes in just once a month.

385
00:27:45,538 --> 00:27:47,831
- She is so inexpensive and she told...
- Come on, Daphne.

386
00:27:47,999 --> 00:27:49,249
Oh, all right.

387
00:27:49,417 --> 00:27:52,586
Say, do you know the one
about the girl tuba player

388
00:27:52,754 --> 00:27:55,547
who was stranded on a desert island
with a one-legged jockey?

389
00:27:55,715 --> 00:27:56,590
No. How does it go?

390
00:27:56,758 --> 00:27:59,093
[Bienstock] Cut it out, girls.
No rough talk.

391
00:27:59,844 --> 00:28:01,845
They went to a conservatory.

392
00:28:02,013 --> 00:28:03,972
[mimics] "They went to a conservatory."

393
00:28:04,140 --> 00:28:06,225
- [grating note]
- [laughter]

394
00:28:07,435 --> 00:28:09,937
How about that talent, huh?

395
00:28:10,563 --> 00:28:13,148
- Like fallin' into a tub of butter.
- Watch it, Daphne.

396
00:28:13,316 --> 00:28:17,361
When I was a kid, Joe, I dreamed I was
locked up overnight in a pastry shop.

397
00:28:17,529 --> 00:28:19,363
And there was goodies all around.

398
00:28:19,531 --> 00:28:24,368
Jelly rolls, mocha éclairs, sponge cake,
and Boston cream pie and cherry tarts...

399
00:28:24,536 --> 00:28:27,955
Listen to me: no butter, no pastry.
We're on a diet.

400
00:28:28,123 --> 00:28:30,124
Yeah, sure, Joe.

401
00:28:30,583 --> 00:28:33,377
Not there. That's the emergency brake.

402
00:28:35,130 --> 00:28:37,214
Now you've done it.
Now you have done it!

403
00:28:37,382 --> 00:28:40,592
- Done what?
- You tore off one of my chests.

404
00:28:41,302 --> 00:28:43,887
- You'd better go get it fixed.
- You'd better come help me.

405
00:28:44,055 --> 00:28:46,181
[train whistle]

406
00:28:52,814 --> 00:28:54,732
This way, Daphne.

407
00:28:54,899 --> 00:28:57,860
Now you tore the other one.

408
00:29:06,745 --> 00:29:07,911
Hm...!

409
00:29:10,039 --> 00:29:11,248
Terribly sorry.

410
00:29:11,416 --> 00:29:13,834
It's OK. I was scared it was Sweet Sue.

411
00:29:14,002 --> 00:29:16,545
- You won't tell anybody, will you?
- [Josephine] Tell what?

412
00:29:16,713 --> 00:29:20,090
If they catch me once more,
they'll kick me out of the band.

413
00:29:21,843 --> 00:29:23,886
Are you the replacement
for the bass and sax?

414
00:29:24,053 --> 00:29:25,888
That's us. And I'm Daphne.

415
00:29:26,055 --> 00:29:28,515
This is... uh... Joe... sephine.

416
00:29:28,683 --> 00:29:30,184
Come in.

417
00:29:30,435 --> 00:29:32,311
- I'm Sugar Cane.
- Hi.

418
00:29:32,479 --> 00:29:35,522
- Sugar Cane?
- I changed it from Sugar Kowalczyk.

419
00:29:35,690 --> 00:29:39,526
- Polish?
- Yes. I come from this musical family.

420
00:29:39,694 --> 00:29:42,112
My mother's a piano teacher.
My father was a conductor.

421
00:29:42,280 --> 00:29:45,449
- Where did he conduct?
- On the Baltimore and Ohio.

422
00:29:45,867 --> 00:29:47,075
Oh.

423
00:29:48,620 --> 00:29:51,955
- I play the ukulele, and I sing, too.
- [Daphne] Sings, too...

424
00:29:52,123 --> 00:29:55,709
I don't have much of a voice,
but this isn't much of a band, either.

425
00:29:55,877 --> 00:29:57,836
I'm only with them
'cause I'm running away.

426
00:29:58,004 --> 00:30:01,799
- Running away from what?
- Oh, don't get me started on that.

427
00:30:01,966 --> 00:30:04,259
Hey, you want some? It's bourbon.

428
00:30:04,761 --> 00:30:07,846
I'll take a rain check.
[nervous chuckling, snorts]

429
00:30:08,598 --> 00:30:09,890
I don't want you to think I'm a drinker.

430
00:30:10,058 --> 00:30:13,185
I can stop any time I want to,
only I don't want to.

431
00:30:13,353 --> 00:30:15,687
- Especially when I'm blue.
- [Josephine] We understand.

432
00:30:15,855 --> 00:30:19,900
All the girls drink. But I'm the one
that gets caught. Story of my life.

433
00:30:20,068 --> 00:30:22,778
I always get the
fuzzy end of the lollipop.

434
00:30:28,159 --> 00:30:29,743
Are my seams straight?

435
00:30:29,911 --> 00:30:31,411
I'll say.

436
00:30:33,748 --> 00:30:35,999
- See you around, girls.
- Bye, Sugar.

437
00:30:36,167 --> 00:30:39,419
[giggling] We have been playing
with the wrong bands.

438
00:30:39,587 --> 00:30:42,256
- Down, Daphne.
- See the shape of that liquor cabinet?

439
00:30:42,423 --> 00:30:45,259
Forget it. One false move
and they'll toss us off the train.

440
00:30:45,426 --> 00:30:48,762
Then it's the police,
the papers and the Mob in Chicago.

441
00:30:48,930 --> 00:30:51,974
Boy, would I love to
borrow a cup of that Sugar.

442
00:30:52,141 --> 00:30:53,600
Look...

443
00:30:53,768 --> 00:30:57,020
No pastry, no butter - and no Sugar.

444
00:30:57,939 --> 00:31:00,440
You tore 'em again.

445
00:31:08,116 --> 00:31:11,285
[♪ playing Runnin' Wild]

446
00:31:18,418 --> 00:31:22,087
[erratic saxophone playing]

447
00:31:38,855 --> 00:31:42,900
Hey, Sheboygan. What was your last job?
Playing square dances?

448
00:31:43,067 --> 00:31:44,943
No. Funerals.

449
00:31:45,111 --> 00:31:48,780
Would you mind rejoining the living?
Goose it up a little.

450
00:31:48,948 --> 00:31:50,324
We'll try.

451
00:31:51,284 --> 00:31:52,993
How did those holes get there?

452
00:31:53,161 --> 00:31:55,621
Uh... Those?

453
00:31:56,998 --> 00:31:58,498
I don't know.
[nervous chuckling]

454
00:31:59,000 --> 00:32:00,000
Mice?

455
00:32:00,793 --> 00:32:04,755
All right, girls. Let's take it from
the top. And put a little heat under it.

456
00:32:05,340 --> 00:32:07,132
[enthusiastic playing]

457
00:32:28,947 --> 00:32:32,032
<i>♪ Runnin' wild, lost control</i>

458
00:32:32,200 --> 00:32:34,701
<i>♪ Runnin' wild, mighty bold</i>

459
00:32:34,869 --> 00:32:38,038
<i>♪ Feelin' gay, reckless too</i>

460
00:32:38,206 --> 00:32:41,208
<i>♪ Carefree mind all the time, never blue</i>

461
00:32:41,376 --> 00:32:44,002
<i>♪ Always goin', don't know where</i>

462
00:32:44,170 --> 00:32:48,298
<i>♪ Always showin' I don't care</i>

463
00:32:48,466 --> 00:32:51,385
<i>♪ Don't love nobody</i>

464
00:32:51,552 --> 00:32:54,554
<i>♪ It's not worthwhile</i>

465
00:32:55,807 --> 00:32:58,392
<i>♪ All alone</i>

466
00:32:59,560 --> 00:33:02,145
<i>♪ Runnin' wild ♪</i>

467
00:33:10,530 --> 00:33:12,572
Bienstock!

468
00:33:13,157 --> 00:33:14,491
Yes, Sue? What is it?

469
00:33:14,659 --> 00:33:18,787
I thought I made it clear that I don't
want any drinking in this outfit.

470
00:33:24,711 --> 00:33:26,920
All right, girls.
Who does this belong to?

471
00:33:27,088 --> 00:33:29,047
Come on, now. Speak up.

472
00:33:29,590 --> 00:33:32,092
- Sugar, I warned you...
- Please, Mr. Bienstock.

473
00:33:32,260 --> 00:33:35,554
This is the last straw. In Kansas you
smuggled liquor in a shampoo bottle.

474
00:33:35,722 --> 00:33:37,389
Before that you had
a pint in your ukulele...

475
00:33:37,557 --> 00:33:39,641
Excuse me, Mr. Bienstock,
could I have my flask, please?

476
00:33:39,809 --> 00:33:42,728
Sure. Pack your things.
At the next station... Your flask?

477
00:33:42,895 --> 00:33:45,939
Yes. Just a little bourbon.
Must have slipped through. [giggles]

478
00:33:47,108 --> 00:33:48,275
Give me that.

479
00:33:48,443 --> 00:33:51,278
Didn't you girls say
you went to a conservatory?

480
00:33:51,446 --> 00:33:55,198
- Oh, yes. For a whole year.
- I thought you said three years.

481
00:33:55,533 --> 00:33:57,868
We got time off for good behavior.

482
00:33:58,453 --> 00:34:01,580
There are two things I will not
put up with during working hours:

483
00:34:01,748 --> 00:34:04,541
one is liquor and the other one is men.

484
00:34:04,709 --> 00:34:05,792
Men?

485
00:34:05,960 --> 00:34:07,753
Oh, you don't have to worry about that.

486
00:34:07,920 --> 00:34:10,172
We wouldn't be caught dead with men.

487
00:34:10,339 --> 00:34:13,300
Rough, hairy beasts with eight hands.

488
00:34:13,468 --> 00:34:16,803
And they all just want
one thing from a girl.

489
00:34:16,971 --> 00:34:19,890
I beg your pardon, miss.

490
00:34:20,058 --> 00:34:23,185
All right, girls. From the top again.

491
00:34:24,353 --> 00:34:28,273
[song resumes]

492
00:34:49,921 --> 00:34:50,837
[indistinct chatter]

493
00:35:01,516 --> 00:35:04,184
- Hortense, dear, good night.
- Good night, Daphne.

494
00:35:04,352 --> 00:35:05,727
Maude, sweet dreams
and pleasant thoughts.

495
00:35:05,895 --> 00:35:07,687
- Good night, Daphne.
- Good night, Gloria.

496
00:35:07,855 --> 00:35:10,774
- Good night, Daphne.
- Dolores, you sleep tight, you hear?

497
00:35:12,693 --> 00:35:16,071
- Nighty-night, Emily.
- Toodle-oo.

498
00:35:18,032 --> 00:35:20,534
How about that "toodle-oo."

499
00:35:20,701 --> 00:35:24,871
Steady, boy. Just keep
tellin' yourself you're a girl.

500
00:35:25,039 --> 00:35:27,707
- I'm a girl. I'm a girl. I'm a girl.
- You're a girl. You're a girl.

501
00:35:27,875 --> 00:35:31,211
I'm a girl. I'm a girl.

502
00:35:31,379 --> 00:35:34,214
- I'm a...
- [chattering, giggling]

503
00:35:34,715 --> 00:35:35,799
Hi.

504
00:35:36,843 --> 00:35:39,094
Get a load of that rhythm section.

505
00:35:40,471 --> 00:35:41,805
I'm a girl.

506
00:35:41,973 --> 00:35:43,974
I'm a girl. I'm a girl.

507
00:35:44,142 --> 00:35:46,226
I'm a girl.

508
00:35:47,812 --> 00:35:49,813
[Daphne] Good night, Sugar.

509
00:35:53,526 --> 00:35:55,318
Good night, honey.

510
00:35:56,904 --> 00:35:59,865
Honey? Hey, she called me "honey."

511
00:36:00,032 --> 00:36:01,449
Ooh, honey.

512
00:36:01,617 --> 00:36:02,617
What are you doin'?

513
00:36:02,785 --> 00:36:05,203
I just wanna make sure
that honey stays in her hive.

514
00:36:05,371 --> 00:36:07,581
There'll be no buzzin' around tonight.

515
00:36:07,748 --> 00:36:10,959
Supposin' I gotta go...
like for a drink of water or something.

516
00:36:11,127 --> 00:36:13,545
- Fight it.
- Well, suppose I lose.

517
00:36:13,713 --> 00:36:17,591
- Suppose it's an emergency.
- Pull the emergency brake.

518
00:36:19,051 --> 00:36:22,762
Hey, Bienstock. You know, there's
something funny about those new girls.

519
00:36:22,930 --> 00:36:24,181
Funny? In what way?

520
00:36:24,348 --> 00:36:26,933
I don't know,
but I can feel it right here.

521
00:36:27,101 --> 00:36:28,393
That's one thing about an ulcer.

522
00:36:28,561 --> 00:36:30,687
It's like having a
burglar alarm go off inside of you.

523
00:36:30,855 --> 00:36:33,648
All right. You watch your ulcers,
I'll watch those two.

524
00:36:33,816 --> 00:36:37,235
OK, everybody settle down and go to bed.
Good night, girls.

525
00:36:38,279 --> 00:36:41,489
- Good night, Daphne.
- Good night, Josephine.

526
00:36:44,160 --> 00:36:46,536
[train whistle]

527
00:36:49,415 --> 00:36:52,292
[sighs] I'm a girl. I'm a girl.

528
00:36:52,460 --> 00:36:54,127
I wish I were dead.

529
00:36:54,295 --> 00:36:58,089
I'm a girl...
I'm a girl... I'm a girl...

530
00:36:58,758 --> 00:37:01,176
<i>[repeating with train rhythm] I'm a</i>
<i>girl... I'm a girl... I'm a girl...</i>

531
00:37:40,883 --> 00:37:42,008
[whispers] Daphne.

532
00:37:48,683 --> 00:37:50,141
Daphne.

533
00:37:52,812 --> 00:37:53,853
Sugar.

534
00:37:54,689 --> 00:37:58,733
I wanted to thank you for
covering up for me. You're a real pal.

535
00:37:59,527 --> 00:38:02,904
Oh... It's nothing. I, uh...

536
00:38:03,072 --> 00:38:05,365
I just thought that
us girls should stick together.

537
00:38:05,533 --> 00:38:08,243
If it wasn't for you,
they'd have kicked me off the train.

538
00:38:08,411 --> 00:38:11,705
I'd be out in the middle of nowhere,
sitting on my ukulele.

539
00:38:11,872 --> 00:38:14,833
Oh... It's freezing outside.

540
00:38:15,001 --> 00:38:18,169
I mean, when I think about you
and your poor ukulele...

541
00:38:18,337 --> 00:38:20,714
If there's ever anything
I can do for you...

542
00:38:20,881 --> 00:38:23,508
I can think of a million things.

543
00:38:26,095 --> 00:38:28,555
- That's one of 'em.
- Shh!

544
00:38:28,723 --> 00:38:31,433
- It's Sweet Sue.
- Mm-hm...

545
00:38:42,903 --> 00:38:44,988
I don't want her
to know we're in cahoots.

546
00:38:45,156 --> 00:38:49,117
Oh, well, we won't tell anybody.
Not even Josephine.

547
00:38:49,285 --> 00:38:51,786
Maybe I'd better stay here
till she goes back to sleep.

548
00:38:51,954 --> 00:38:54,456
You stay here as long as you like.

549
00:38:57,835 --> 00:38:59,669
I'm not crowding you, am I?

550
00:38:59,837 --> 00:39:03,089
No. It's nice and cozy.
[nervous chuckling, snorts]

551
00:39:03,257 --> 00:39:05,633
When I was a little girl,
on cold nights like this,

552
00:39:05,801 --> 00:39:07,635
I'd crawl into bed with my sister.

553
00:39:07,803 --> 00:39:11,097
We'd cuddle up under the covers and
pretend we were lost in a dark cave

554
00:39:11,265 --> 00:39:13,433
and were trying to find our way out.
[giggling]

555
00:39:13,601 --> 00:39:16,019
[giggles nervously] Very interesting.

556
00:39:17,813 --> 00:39:21,024
- Anything wrong?
- No, no. Not a thing.

557
00:39:23,194 --> 00:39:25,236
You poor thing.
You're trembling all over.

558
00:39:25,404 --> 00:39:27,280
That's ridiculous.

559
00:39:27,656 --> 00:39:30,283
- Your head's hot.
- That's ridiculous.

560
00:39:31,118 --> 00:39:33,453
- You've got cold feet.
- Isn't that ridiculous?

561
00:39:33,621 --> 00:39:35,955
Here, let me warm them up a little.

562
00:39:36,123 --> 00:39:40,085
- There. Isn't that better?
- Yes. I'm a girl... I'm a girl...

563
00:39:40,252 --> 00:39:42,545
- What'd you say?
- I'm a very sick girl.

564
00:39:42,713 --> 00:39:44,089
I'd better go before
I catch something.

565
00:39:44,256 --> 00:39:45,215
I'm not that sick.

566
00:39:45,383 --> 00:39:46,966
I've got very low resistance.

567
00:39:47,134 --> 00:39:51,429
Uh... Sugar, if you feel you're
coming down with something, my dear,

568
00:39:51,597 --> 00:39:54,474
the best thing in the world
is a shot of whiskey.

569
00:39:54,642 --> 00:39:57,477
- You've got some?
- I know where to get it. [giggles]

570
00:39:57,645 --> 00:39:59,270
Don't move. Shh!

571
00:40:00,064 --> 00:40:02,315
- Hold on.
- OK.

572
00:40:24,004 --> 00:40:25,505
Up. Up.

573
00:40:27,842 --> 00:40:29,342
[thud]

574
00:40:31,512 --> 00:40:34,139
- Are you all right?
- I'm fine.

575
00:40:34,306 --> 00:40:36,891
- How's the bottle?
- Half-full.

576
00:40:38,310 --> 00:40:40,478
- You'd better get some cups.
- Cups?

577
00:40:50,698 --> 00:40:54,534
Oh, I tell you, my dear,
this is the only way to travel.

578
00:40:54,702 --> 00:40:57,370
Put on the lights.
I can't see what I'm doing.

579
00:40:57,538 --> 00:41:00,039
No lights. We don't want them
to know we're having a party.

580
00:41:00,207 --> 00:41:02,709
- But I might spill some.
- So spill it.

581
00:41:02,877 --> 00:41:05,628
Spills, thrills, laughs and games.

582
00:41:06,505 --> 00:41:08,590
This may even turn out
to be a surprise party.

583
00:41:08,757 --> 00:41:11,092
- What's the surprise?
- Uh-uh. Not yet.

584
00:41:11,260 --> 00:41:13,845
- When?
- Better have a drink first.

585
00:41:14,555 --> 00:41:15,889
That'll put hair on your chest.

586
00:41:16,056 --> 00:41:17,807
No fair guessing.

587
00:41:20,019 --> 00:41:21,811
Is this a private clambake,
or can anybody join?

588
00:41:21,979 --> 00:41:23,688
Yes, it's private. Please, go away.

589
00:41:23,856 --> 00:41:26,065
Dolores, do you still
have that bottle of vermouth?

590
00:41:26,233 --> 00:41:27,984
- Sure.
- Who needs vermouth?

591
00:41:28,152 --> 00:41:30,320
We've got bourbon.
We can make Manhattans.

592
00:41:30,488 --> 00:41:33,448
- OK.
- Manhattans? At this time of night?

593
00:41:33,616 --> 00:41:36,242
- Bring the cocktail shaker.
- Oh, Sugar.

594
00:41:36,410 --> 00:41:38,286
You're gonna spoil my surprise.

595
00:41:40,331 --> 00:41:42,415
- Hey, honey, what's up?
- Party in upper 7.

596
00:41:42,583 --> 00:41:44,292
A party?
I'll get cheese and crackers.

597
00:41:44,460 --> 00:41:46,252
I'll get a cocktail shaker,
you get a corkscrew.

598
00:41:46,420 --> 00:41:48,588
OK. Hey, Rosella,
there's a party in upper 7.

599
00:41:48,756 --> 00:41:49,964
- Yeah?
- You got a corkscrew?

600
00:41:50,132 --> 00:41:52,175
- No, but Stella has.
- Well, go get some paper cups.

601
00:41:52,343 --> 00:41:53,426
OK.

602
00:41:53,886 --> 00:41:56,638
- Hey, there's a party in upper 7.
- Party in upper 7.

603
00:42:01,602 --> 00:42:03,311
- Here's the vermouth.
- This is a private party.

604
00:42:03,479 --> 00:42:04,562
Will you please go away?

605
00:42:04,730 --> 00:42:07,232
I brought some cheese and crackers
in case anybody gets hungry.

606
00:42:07,399 --> 00:42:08,983
- What is this?
- Will ten cups be enough?

607
00:42:09,151 --> 00:42:12,111
This is a party for two. Ten cups?
What is...?

608
00:42:12,988 --> 00:42:16,699
- Please, girls. Will you stop this?
- Could you use some Southern Comfort?

609
00:42:16,867 --> 00:42:18,368
Southern Comf...? Shh!

610
00:42:18,536 --> 00:42:21,579
Girls, you'll wake up
the neighbors downstairs.

611
00:42:21,747 --> 00:42:24,040
Watch that corkscrew.

612
00:42:24,208 --> 00:42:26,960
- Here's a cracker.
- No crackers in bed.

613
00:42:27,628 --> 00:42:30,213
Will you girls go away
and form your own party?

614
00:42:30,381 --> 00:42:31,839
Here's the cocktail shaker.

615
00:42:32,007 --> 00:42:35,802
- I wish we had some ice.
- Hey, easy on the vermouth.

616
00:42:35,970 --> 00:42:39,639
13 girls in a berth is bad luck.
12 of you will have to get out.

617
00:42:39,807 --> 00:42:42,684
- Pass me the peanut butter.
- Anyone for salami?

618
00:42:43,644 --> 00:42:46,145
No more food.
I'll have ants in the morning.

619
00:42:47,439 --> 00:42:50,191
Hey. Have you got any
maraschino cherries on you?

620
00:42:50,359 --> 00:42:52,860
- Hm?
- Oh, never mind.

621
00:42:55,739 --> 00:42:58,491
[girls chattering and laughing]

622
00:42:59,660 --> 00:43:01,786
Maraschino cherries?

623
00:43:10,713 --> 00:43:12,213
What's going on here?

624
00:43:12,381 --> 00:43:16,175
Daphne. Daphne, where are you?
Daphne?

625
00:43:17,011 --> 00:43:19,679
It's not my fault. I didn't invite 'em.

626
00:43:19,847 --> 00:43:21,097
Come on, girls, break it up.

627
00:43:22,349 --> 00:43:26,352
You heard Josephine. Girls.
Everybody out. Everybody out.

628
00:43:27,104 --> 00:43:29,939
- Not you, Sugar.
- I'm going to get some ice.

629
00:43:30,107 --> 00:43:31,941
Get out. Get out!

630
00:43:32,109 --> 00:43:35,028
That's right, Sugar.
Now the rest of you. Out.

631
00:43:36,030 --> 00:43:37,864
- Shh!
- Come on in. The water's fine.

632
00:43:38,032 --> 00:43:39,032
Have a Manhattan.

633
00:43:39,199 --> 00:43:42,994
- Pipe down. We'll all be fired.
- Sugar. Don't leave me here alone.

634
00:43:43,162 --> 00:43:45,371
[Josephine] Come on, kids.
Give up, will ya? It's two o'clock.

635
00:43:45,539 --> 00:43:49,584
You've had your fun.
The party's over. Everybody go home.

636
00:43:49,752 --> 00:43:52,920
- What's this?
- Josephine, over here before it melts.

637
00:44:00,012 --> 00:44:01,262
Put it here.

638
00:44:02,348 --> 00:44:04,599
Sugar, you're gonna
get yourself into a lot of trouble.

639
00:44:04,767 --> 00:44:06,225
Yeah, you'd better keep a lookout.

640
00:44:06,393 --> 00:44:08,603
If Bienstock catches you again...

641
00:44:09,063 --> 00:44:11,022
What's the matter with you, anyway?

642
00:44:11,190 --> 00:44:13,316
I'm not very bright, I guess.

643
00:44:13,484 --> 00:44:15,693
I wouldn't say that. Careless, maybe.

644
00:44:15,861 --> 00:44:17,445
No, just dumb. If I had any brains,

645
00:44:17,613 --> 00:44:20,657
I wouldn't be on this crummy train
with this crummy girls' band.

646
00:44:20,824 --> 00:44:22,492
Well, why'd you take this job?

647
00:44:22,660 --> 00:44:25,578
I used to sing with male bands,
but I can't afford it anymore.

648
00:44:25,746 --> 00:44:28,081
Have you ever been with a male band?

649
00:44:28,248 --> 00:44:29,707
Who, me?

650
00:44:29,875 --> 00:44:31,250
That's what I'm running away from.

651
00:44:31,418 --> 00:44:35,213
I worked with six in the last two years.
Oh, brother.

652
00:44:35,381 --> 00:44:36,964
- Rough?
- I'll say.

653
00:44:37,132 --> 00:44:40,385
- You can't trust those guys.
- I can't trust myself.

654
00:44:40,552 --> 00:44:43,054
I have this thing
about saxophone players.

655
00:44:43,222 --> 00:44:45,306
Especially tenor sax.

656
00:44:47,184 --> 00:44:50,603
- Really?
- I don't know why, but they curdle me.

657
00:44:50,771 --> 00:44:54,190
All they have to do is play eight bars
<i>of Come To Me, My Melancholy Baby</i>

658
00:44:54,358 --> 00:44:55,566
and my spine turns to custard.

659
00:44:55,734 --> 00:44:58,277
I get goose-pimply all over,
and I come to 'em.

660
00:44:58,445 --> 00:45:00,780
- That so?
- Every time.

661
00:45:02,282 --> 00:45:04,283
You know, I play tenor sax.

662
00:45:04,451 --> 00:45:08,621
But you're a girl - thank goodness.
That's why I joined this band.

663
00:45:08,789 --> 00:45:11,958
Safety first.
Anything to get away from those bums.

664
00:45:12,126 --> 00:45:14,210
- Yeah.
- You don't know what they're like.

665
00:45:14,378 --> 00:45:16,129
You fall for 'em. You really love 'em.

666
00:45:16,296 --> 00:45:19,465
You think this is gonna be the
biggest thing since the Graf Zeppelin.

667
00:45:19,633 --> 00:45:21,926
The next thing you know,
they're borrowing money from you,

668
00:45:22,094 --> 00:45:24,929
spending it on other dames
and betting on horses.

669
00:45:25,639 --> 00:45:26,556
You don't say.

670
00:45:26,724 --> 00:45:30,143
Then one morning you wake up,
the guy's gone, the saxophone's gone.

671
00:45:30,310 --> 00:45:32,019
All that's left is a pair of old socks

672
00:45:32,187 --> 00:45:35,064
and a tube of toothpaste
all squeezed out.

673
00:45:35,232 --> 00:45:37,984
So, you pull yourself together,
you go on to the next job,

674
00:45:38,152 --> 00:45:39,694
the next saxophone player.

675
00:45:39,862 --> 00:45:41,988
It's the same thing all over again.

676
00:45:42,156 --> 00:45:45,616
You see what I mean? Not very bright.

677
00:45:46,160 --> 00:45:48,369
Brains aren't everything.

678
00:45:48,829 --> 00:45:52,331
I can tell you one thing. It's not
gonna happen to me again - ever.

679
00:45:52,499 --> 00:45:55,668
I'm tired of getting
the fuzzy end of the lollipop.

680
00:45:55,836 --> 00:45:58,921
Ice. What's keeping the ice?
The natives are getting restless.

681
00:46:00,007 --> 00:46:02,592
- How about a couple of drinks for us?
- Sure.

682
00:46:04,178 --> 00:46:07,013
- You know, I'm gonna be 25 in June.
- You are?

683
00:46:07,181 --> 00:46:09,849
That's a quarter of a century.
Makes a girl think.

684
00:46:10,017 --> 00:46:11,976
- About what?
- About the future.

685
00:46:12,144 --> 00:46:15,229
You know - like a husband. That's why
I'm glad we're going to Florida.

686
00:46:15,397 --> 00:46:18,733
- What's in Florida?
- Millionaires. Flocks of them.

687
00:46:18,901 --> 00:46:21,235
They all go south for the winter,
like birds.

688
00:46:21,403 --> 00:46:24,572
- Gonna catch yourself a rich bird?
- Oh, I don't care how rich he is.

689
00:46:24,740 --> 00:46:28,993
As long as he has a yacht, a private
railroad car and his own toothpaste.

690
00:46:29,161 --> 00:46:32,330
- You're entitled.
- Maybe you'll meet one too, Josephine.

691
00:46:32,498 --> 00:46:36,083
With money like Rockefeller and
shoulders like Johnny Weissmuller.

692
00:46:36,251 --> 00:46:39,378
- Oh, I want mine to wear glasses.
- Glasses?

693
00:46:39,546 --> 00:46:43,216
Men who wear glasses are so much
more gentle and sweet and helpless.

694
00:46:43,383 --> 00:46:46,594
- Haven't you ever noticed it?
- Now that you've mentioned it. Hm-hm.

695
00:46:46,762 --> 00:46:48,554
They get those weak eyes from reading.

696
00:46:48,722 --> 00:46:53,643
You know, those long, tiny little
columns in The Wall Street Journal.

697
00:46:54,561 --> 00:46:57,480
That bass fiddle, she sure
knows how to throw a party.

698
00:46:57,648 --> 00:46:59,690
Hot-diggety-dog.

699
00:47:00,984 --> 00:47:02,735
Well, happy days.

700
00:47:03,570 --> 00:47:07,740
I hope this time you wind up
with the sweet end of the lollipop.

701
00:47:09,409 --> 00:47:11,035
[giggling, chatter]

702
00:47:11,203 --> 00:47:13,371
So the one-legged jockey said...

703
00:47:13,539 --> 00:47:17,041
- What did he say?
- So the one-legged jockey said:

704
00:47:17,209 --> 00:47:20,795
"Don't worry about me, baby.
I ride side-saddle."

705
00:47:20,963 --> 00:47:23,381
[squealing laughter]

706
00:47:23,549 --> 00:47:25,174
Oh, shh!

707
00:47:25,342 --> 00:47:26,968
[hiccupping]

708
00:47:28,345 --> 00:47:30,429
I'm terribly sorry.
I seem to have hiccups.

709
00:47:30,597 --> 00:47:33,015
Hey, let's rub some ice on her neck.

710
00:47:33,183 --> 00:47:35,101
I think... Ow! You dropped it.

711
00:47:35,269 --> 00:47:36,811
Oh, that's cold.

712
00:47:36,979 --> 00:47:39,605
- Oh, no, please. Don't do that.
- She's ticklish.

713
00:47:39,773 --> 00:47:41,691
[girls squeal with delight]

714
00:47:44,152 --> 00:47:48,531
Help. Help. Help. Josephine.

715
00:47:48,699 --> 00:47:52,952
Please stop that. Stop that.
Stop that!

716
00:47:58,792 --> 00:48:00,209
[all yelling]

717
00:48:02,713 --> 00:48:04,755
- What happened?
- Search me.

718
00:48:04,923 --> 00:48:07,008
Uh... I mean, I'll see.

719
00:48:08,552 --> 00:48:10,845
[all chattering]

720
00:48:17,603 --> 00:48:19,812
All right, what's goin' on around here?

721
00:48:19,980 --> 00:48:21,981
Bienstock!

722
00:48:22,983 --> 00:48:25,026
Are we in Florida?

723
00:48:25,485 --> 00:48:27,737
[girls singing]
<i>♪ Down among the sheltering palms</i>

724
00:48:28,572 --> 00:48:31,741
<i>♪ Honey, wait for me</i>

725
00:48:31,909 --> 00:48:34,827
<i>♪ Don't be forgettin' we got a date</i>

726
00:48:34,995 --> 00:48:37,997
<i>♪ Up where the sun</i>
<i>goes down about eight</i>

727
00:48:38,165 --> 00:48:41,334
<i>♪ How my love is</i>
<i>burning, burning, burning</i>

728
00:48:41,501 --> 00:48:44,128
<i>♪ How my heart is</i>
<i>yearning, yearning, yearning</i>

729
00:48:44,296 --> 00:48:47,173
<i>♪ To be down among the sheltering palms</i>

730
00:48:47,341 --> 00:48:50,843
<i>♪ Honey, wait for me ♪</i>

731
00:48:51,678 --> 00:48:54,347
[giggling and squealing]

732
00:49:10,072 --> 00:49:13,950
Sugar?
Here. I'll carry the instruments.

733
00:49:14,117 --> 00:49:16,702
- Oh, thank you, Daphne.
- Oh, thank you, Daphne.

734
00:49:16,870 --> 00:49:18,537
Isn't she a sweetheart?

735
00:49:25,337 --> 00:49:26,796
How do you do?

736
00:49:30,634 --> 00:49:31,842
Zowie!

737
00:49:32,010 --> 00:49:35,513
There they are. More millionaires
than you can shake a stick at.

738
00:49:35,681 --> 00:49:37,556
I bet there isn't one under 75.

739
00:49:37,724 --> 00:49:41,060
That's three quarters of a century.
Makes a girl think.

740
00:49:41,228 --> 00:49:42,937
Let's hope they brought
their grandsons along.

741
00:49:43,105 --> 00:49:45,189
[chortles] Yes.

742
00:49:54,574 --> 00:49:56,033
Oh, pardon me, miss.

743
00:49:58,328 --> 00:50:00,329
- May I?
- Help yourself.

744
00:50:00,497 --> 00:50:03,207
I'm Osgood Fielding the Third.

745
00:50:03,375 --> 00:50:05,418
I'm Cinderella the Second.

746
00:50:05,585 --> 00:50:09,839
If there's one thing I admire,
it's a girl with a shapely ankle.

747
00:50:10,340 --> 00:50:12,591
[chuckles] Me, too. Bye-bye.

748
00:50:13,385 --> 00:50:16,512
- Let me carry one of the instruments.
- Oh, thank you.

749
00:50:16,680 --> 00:50:19,181
Aren't you a sweetheart.

750
00:50:23,937 --> 00:50:26,647
It certainly is delightful
having young blood around here.

751
00:50:26,815 --> 00:50:28,733
Well, personally, I'm type O.

752
00:50:28,900 --> 00:50:31,318
You know, I've always been
fascinated by show business.

753
00:50:31,486 --> 00:50:33,029
- Is that so?
- Yes.

754
00:50:33,196 --> 00:50:36,365
As a matter of fact, it's cost
my family quite a bit of money.

755
00:50:36,533 --> 00:50:39,452
- Oh, you invest in shows?
- Showgirls.

756
00:50:39,619 --> 00:50:41,120
I've been married
seven or eight times.

757
00:50:41,288 --> 00:50:44,582
- You're not sure?
- Mama is keeping score.

758
00:50:44,750 --> 00:50:47,501
- She's getting annoyed with me.
- I wouldn't wonder.

759
00:50:47,669 --> 00:50:49,712
So this year, when the
<i>George White's Scandals opened,</i>

760
00:50:49,880 --> 00:50:51,255
she packed me off to Florida.

761
00:50:51,423 --> 00:50:56,427
Right now she thinks I'm out
on my yacht, deep-sea fishing.

762
00:50:57,262 --> 00:51:01,682
Well, pull in your reel, Mr. Fielding.
You're barking up the wrong fish.

763
00:51:03,018 --> 00:51:06,062
If I promise not to be a naughty boy,
how about dinner tonight?

764
00:51:06,229 --> 00:51:09,273
- I'm sorry. I'll be on the bandstand.
- Oh, of course.

765
00:51:09,441 --> 00:51:11,942
- Which instrument do you play?
- Bull fiddle.

766
00:51:12,110 --> 00:51:13,527
Oh, fascinating.

767
00:51:13,695 --> 00:51:15,988
Do you use a bow,
or do you just pluck it?

768
00:51:16,990 --> 00:51:20,076
Most of the time, I slap it.
[chuckling]

769
00:51:20,243 --> 00:51:21,994
You must be quite a girl.

770
00:51:22,829 --> 00:51:24,622
- Wanna bet?
- [both chuckling]

771
00:51:24,790 --> 00:51:28,501
My last wife was an acrobatic dancer.
You know, sort of a contortionist.

772
00:51:28,668 --> 00:51:32,088
She could smoke a cigarette
while holding it between her toes.

773
00:51:32,255 --> 00:51:33,631
Zowie!

774
00:51:33,799 --> 00:51:35,800
- But Mama broke it up.
- Why?

775
00:51:35,967 --> 00:51:38,260
She doesn't approve of girls who smoke.

776
00:51:40,263 --> 00:51:42,473
- Bye-bye, Mr. Fielding.
- Bye-bye?

777
00:51:42,641 --> 00:51:45,684
- This is where I get off.
- Oh, no. No, no, no.

778
00:51:45,852 --> 00:51:47,853
You don't get off that easy.

779
00:51:48,021 --> 00:51:50,564
All right, driver.
Once around the park, slowly.

780
00:51:50,732 --> 00:51:52,858
And keep your eyes on the road.

781
00:52:02,786 --> 00:52:05,496
What kind of a girl
do you think I am, Mr. Fielding?

782
00:52:06,915 --> 00:52:10,084
- Oh, please. It won't happen again.
- I'll say.

783
00:52:10,252 --> 00:52:12,753
- Please, come back.
- I'll walk, thank you.

784
00:52:12,921 --> 00:52:15,005
Oh, please, miss...

785
00:52:17,592 --> 00:52:19,135
Zowie!

786
00:52:19,386 --> 00:52:22,179
All right, girls. Here are
your room assignments.

787
00:52:22,347 --> 00:52:25,099
My glasses. Where are my glasses?

788
00:52:26,268 --> 00:52:28,060
Olga and Mary Lou are in 412.

789
00:52:28,228 --> 00:52:31,021
And, Mary Lou, will you keep your kimono
buttoned when you ring for room service?

790
00:52:31,189 --> 00:52:33,482
- Well!
- Josephine and Daphne are in 413.

791
00:52:33,650 --> 00:52:35,860
- Thank you.
- Dolores and Sugar in 414.

792
00:52:36,027 --> 00:52:37,194
Me and Sugar?

793
00:52:37,362 --> 00:52:39,697
What did you expect?
A one-legged jockey?

794
00:52:39,865 --> 00:52:41,699
Rosella and Emily in 415...

795
00:52:42,534 --> 00:52:44,910
- I wish they'd put us in the same room.
- So do I.

796
00:52:45,078 --> 00:52:48,581
But don't worry about it, Sugar.
We'll see a lot of each other.

797
00:52:49,708 --> 00:52:54,211
414... That's the same room number
I had in Cincinnati,

798
00:52:54,379 --> 00:52:56,463
my last time around with a male band.

799
00:52:56,631 --> 00:52:58,215
What a heel he was.

800
00:52:58,383 --> 00:53:02,136
- A saxophone player?
- What else? Was I ever crazy about him.

801
00:53:02,304 --> 00:53:05,264
At two in the morning he sent me down
for hot dogs and potato salad.

802
00:53:05,432 --> 00:53:08,017
They were out of potato salad,
so I brought coleslaw.

803
00:53:08,185 --> 00:53:12,104
- So he threw it right in my face.
- Forget saxophone players.

804
00:53:12,272 --> 00:53:14,773
You're gonna meet
a millionaire - a young one.

805
00:53:14,941 --> 00:53:18,777
- What makes you so sure?
- [chuckles] My feminine intuition.

806
00:53:26,661 --> 00:53:29,246
- Oh. Are these your bags?
- Mm-hm.

807
00:53:30,081 --> 00:53:33,292
- And that one, too.
- OK, doll.

808
00:53:34,252 --> 00:53:37,463
- I suppose you want a tip.
- Ah, forget it, doll.

809
00:53:37,631 --> 00:53:39,882
After all, you work here
and I work here.

810
00:53:40,050 --> 00:53:42,927
Believe you me, it's nice to
have you with the organization.

811
00:53:43,094 --> 00:53:45,054
- Bye-bye.
- Listen, doll.

812
00:53:45,222 --> 00:53:48,140
- What time do you get off tonight?
- Why?

813
00:53:48,308 --> 00:53:51,560
I'm workin' the night shift and
I got a bottle of gin stashed away.

814
00:53:51,728 --> 00:53:52,645
When there's a lull...

815
00:53:52,812 --> 00:53:55,231
Don't you think you're
a little young for that, sonny?

816
00:53:55,398 --> 00:53:58,984
Oh, you wanna see my driver's license?

817
00:53:59,986 --> 00:54:01,445
Get lost, will you?

818
00:54:01,613 --> 00:54:04,990
That's the way I like 'em -
big and sassy.

819
00:54:05,742 --> 00:54:08,369
Oh, and, uh... get rid of your roommate.

820
00:54:12,374 --> 00:54:13,666
[sighs]

821
00:54:23,426 --> 00:54:25,302
- Dirty old man.
- What happened?

822
00:54:25,470 --> 00:54:28,764
- I just got pinched in the elevator.
- Now you know how the other half lives.

823
00:54:28,932 --> 00:54:30,099
Look at that. I'm not even pretty.

824
00:54:30,267 --> 00:54:32,309
They don't care,
so long as you're wearing a skirt.

825
00:54:32,477 --> 00:54:34,395
It's like waving a red flag
in front of a bull.

826
00:54:34,562 --> 00:54:37,064
Really? Well, I'm sick of being
the flag. I wanna be a bull again.

827
00:54:37,232 --> 00:54:38,274
What do you say? Let's get outta here.

828
00:54:38,441 --> 00:54:39,525
- Let's blow.
- Blow where?

829
00:54:39,693 --> 00:54:43,028
You promised me that the minute
we hit Florida we were gonna beat it.

830
00:54:43,196 --> 00:54:47,241
- How can we? We're broke.
- We can find another band. A male band.

831
00:54:47,409 --> 00:54:48,409
Look, stupid...

832
00:54:48,576 --> 00:54:52,538
Right now, Spats Colombo is looking for
us in every male band in the country.

833
00:54:52,706 --> 00:54:55,791
- It's so humiliating.
- So you got pinched. So what?

834
00:54:55,959 --> 00:54:57,751
Would you rather be
picking lead out of your navel?

835
00:54:57,919 --> 00:55:00,754
All right, all right. But how long
do you think we keep this up?

836
00:55:00,922 --> 00:55:03,632
- What's the beef? We're sittin' pretty.
- Huh?

837
00:55:03,800 --> 00:55:07,094
Look. We get room and board.
We're getting paid every week. Look.

838
00:55:07,262 --> 00:55:09,722
Look at the palm trees, flying fish...

839
00:55:09,889 --> 00:55:12,016
What are you givin' me with flyin' fish?

840
00:55:12,183 --> 00:55:14,476
I know why you wanna stay.
You're after Sugar.

841
00:55:14,644 --> 00:55:17,855
- Me, after Sugar?
- I saw the both of you in that bus.

842
00:55:18,023 --> 00:55:21,025
All lovey-dovey and whisperin'
and borrowin' each other's lipstick.

843
00:55:21,192 --> 00:55:22,067
I saw you!

844
00:55:22,235 --> 00:55:24,236
- What are you saying? Me and Sugar?
- You and Sugar.

845
00:55:24,404 --> 00:55:28,198
- We're just like sisters.
- Well, I'm your fairy godmother.

846
00:55:28,366 --> 00:55:30,034
And I'm gonna keep an eye on you.

847
00:55:30,201 --> 00:55:33,162
- [knocking]
- [Bienstock] Are you decent?

848
00:55:38,960 --> 00:55:39,960
Come in.

849
00:55:41,713 --> 00:55:43,964
You girls seen a brown bag
with a white stripe and my initials?

850
00:55:44,132 --> 00:55:46,633
- A what?
- My suitcase with my resort clothes.

851
00:55:46,801 --> 00:55:49,261
- No, we haven't.
- I can't understand it.

852
00:55:49,429 --> 00:55:51,930
First my glasses disappear,
then one of my suitcases.

853
00:55:52,098 --> 00:55:53,974
- Where's my ukulele?
- Now a ukulele.

854
00:55:54,142 --> 00:55:55,768
There must be a
sneak thief around here.

855
00:55:55,935 --> 00:55:58,729
Oh! Here it is. Hi, Sug.

856
00:55:58,897 --> 00:56:01,190
A bunch of us girls are gonna
go for a swim. Wanna come along?

857
00:56:01,358 --> 00:56:02,691
A swim. Oh, you betcha.

858
00:56:02,859 --> 00:56:05,444
Just a minute, Daphne.
You haven't got a bathing suit.

859
00:56:05,612 --> 00:56:07,279
She doesn't need one.
I don't have one either.

860
00:56:07,447 --> 00:56:09,948
See? She doesn't have one either.
You don't?

861
00:56:10,116 --> 00:56:12,534
We can rent some at the bathhouse.
How about you, Josephine?

862
00:56:12,702 --> 00:56:15,204
No, thanks. I think I'll stay in
and soak in a hot tub.

863
00:56:15,372 --> 00:56:18,957
- On a day like this? It's lovely out.
- Yeah, well, let her soak. Come on.

864
00:56:19,793 --> 00:56:22,920
- Don't get burned, Daphne.
- Oh, I've got suntan lotion.

865
00:56:23,088 --> 00:56:27,132
See? She'll rub it on me, I'll rub it
on her, we'll rub it on each other.

866
00:56:27,300 --> 00:56:28,759
Bye-bye.

867
00:57:13,680 --> 00:57:17,057
[girls singing] ♪ By the sea,
<i>by the sea, by the beautiful sea</i>

868
00:57:18,017 --> 00:57:20,686
<i>♪ You and me, you and me,</i>
<i>oh, how happy we'll be</i>

869
00:57:20,854 --> 00:57:23,480
<i>♪ I love to be beside,</i>
<i>beside, beside the sea</i>

870
00:57:23,648 --> 00:57:26,859
<i>♪ Beside the seaside</i>
<i>by the beautiful sea ♪</i>

871
00:57:30,405 --> 00:57:34,324
Daphne. Cut it out.
What do you think you're doing?

872
00:57:34,492 --> 00:57:37,536
Just a little trick I picked up
in the elevator. [cackling]

873
00:57:37,704 --> 00:57:40,038
Ooh, look out. Here comes a big one.

874
00:57:40,206 --> 00:57:41,582
Whee!

875
00:57:52,927 --> 00:57:54,928
[girls squealing, chattering]

876
00:58:11,237 --> 00:58:14,198
Daphne. I had no idea
you were such a big girl.

877
00:58:14,365 --> 00:58:16,825
Oh, you should've seen me
before I went on a diet.

878
00:58:16,993 --> 00:58:18,702
I mean your shoulders and your arms.

879
00:58:18,870 --> 00:58:21,663
That's from carrying
that bull fiddle around all day.

880
00:58:21,831 --> 00:58:24,082
- There's one thing I envy you for.
- What's that?

881
00:58:24,250 --> 00:58:26,168
You're so flat-chested.

882
00:58:26,336 --> 00:58:29,087
Clothes hang better on you
than they do on me.

883
00:58:29,589 --> 00:58:31,215
[Dolores] Watch out, Daphne.

884
00:58:31,674 --> 00:58:34,301
- Sugar, come on. Let's play ball.
- OK!

885
00:58:35,762 --> 00:58:37,304
Let's go, Junior, time for your nap.

886
00:58:37,472 --> 00:58:39,765
No. I wanna play.

887
00:58:39,933 --> 00:58:42,142
You heard your mother, Junior. Scram!

888
00:58:42,310 --> 00:58:44,937
This beach ain't big enough
for the both of us. Get outta here.

889
00:58:45,104 --> 00:58:47,689
Mommy! Mommy!

890
00:58:47,857 --> 00:58:48,857
[Daphne] Here we go.

891
00:58:49,025 --> 00:58:52,110
[girls chant] I like coffee, I like tea.

892
00:58:52,278 --> 00:58:56,281
How many boys are stuck on me?

893
00:58:56,449 --> 00:58:59,326
One, two, three,

894
00:58:59,494 --> 00:59:02,538
four, five, six, seven...

895
00:59:02,705 --> 00:59:04,331
[squealing]

896
00:59:08,628 --> 00:59:11,380
[Cary Grant voice] I'm terribly sorry.
You're not hurt, are you?

897
00:59:11,548 --> 00:59:13,423
- I don't think so.
- I wish you'd make sure.

898
00:59:13,591 --> 00:59:16,093
- Why?
- Because when people find out who I am,

899
00:59:16,261 --> 00:59:18,136
they get themselves a wheelchair,
a shyster lawyer

900
00:59:18,304 --> 00:59:20,973
and sue me for three
quarters of a million dollars.

901
00:59:21,599 --> 00:59:23,809
Don't worry, I won't sue you,
no matter who you are.

902
00:59:23,977 --> 00:59:25,060
Thank you.

903
00:59:27,230 --> 00:59:30,065
- Who are you?
- Now, really!

904
00:59:31,651 --> 00:59:33,318
[Daphne] Sugar!

905
00:59:33,486 --> 00:59:35,028
Come on.

906
00:59:35,697 --> 00:59:36,905
Honestly.

907
00:59:38,324 --> 00:59:39,783
Cheerio.

908
00:59:44,998 --> 00:59:48,000
- Haven't I seen you somewhere before?
- Not very likely.

909
00:59:48,167 --> 00:59:50,794
- Are you staying at the hotel?
- Not at all.

910
00:59:50,962 --> 00:59:52,671
Your face is familiar.

911
00:59:52,839 --> 00:59:55,132
Possible you've seen it
in newspapers or magazines.

912
00:59:55,300 --> 00:59:58,552
<i>- Uh... Vanity Fair.</i>
- That must be it.

913
00:59:58,720 --> 01:00:02,180
Would you mind moving just a little,
please? You're blocking my view.

914
01:00:02,348 --> 01:00:03,557
Your view? Of what?

915
01:00:03,725 --> 01:00:07,519
They run up a red-and-white flag on
the yacht when it's time for cocktails.

916
01:00:07,687 --> 01:00:09,855
You own a yacht?

917
01:00:10,732 --> 01:00:13,066
Which one is it? The big one?

918
01:00:13,651 --> 01:00:15,485
Certainly not.
With all the unrest in the world,

919
01:00:15,653 --> 01:00:18,530
I don't think anybody should have
a yacht that sleeps more than 12.

920
01:00:19,532 --> 01:00:21,366
I quite agree.

921
01:00:21,534 --> 01:00:23,744
Tell me, who runs up that flag?

922
01:00:23,911 --> 01:00:26,038
- Your wife?
- No, my flag steward.

923
01:00:26,914 --> 01:00:29,416
Who mixes the cocktails? Your wife?

924
01:00:29,959 --> 01:00:32,044
No, my cocktail steward.

925
01:00:32,211 --> 01:00:34,838
Look, if you're interested
in whether I am married or not...

926
01:00:35,006 --> 01:00:37,883
