And I intend to keep it that way.

1149
01:13:05,381 --> 01:13:07,090
- Good luck.
- Thanks.

1150
01:13:12,471 --> 01:13:15,932
[♪ musical finale]

1151
01:13:17,351 --> 01:13:19,811
[applause]

1152
01:14:37,389 --> 01:14:40,266
But it's such a waste.
A full moon, an empty yacht.

1153
01:14:40,434 --> 01:14:42,810
- I'll throw up.
- Then let's go dancing.

1154
01:14:42,978 --> 01:14:45,688
- There's a roadhouse down the coast...
- [horn beeps]

1155
01:14:49,610 --> 01:14:52,570
Well, I'll be...
He does have a bicycle.

1156
01:14:52,738 --> 01:14:54,030
- Who?
- Hm?

1157
01:14:54,865 --> 01:14:56,741
- About the roadhouse?
- Oh!

1158
01:14:56,909 --> 01:14:59,160
They have a Cuban band
that's the berries.

1159
01:14:59,328 --> 01:15:03,331
Let's go there, blindfold the orchestra
and tango till dawn.

1160
01:15:03,499 --> 01:15:05,500
- You know something, Mr. Fielding?
- What?

1161
01:15:05,667 --> 01:15:06,918
You're dynamite.

1162
01:15:07,794 --> 01:15:10,338
You're a pretty hot
little firecracker yourself.

1163
01:15:10,506 --> 01:15:11,756
[barks]

1164
01:16:03,267 --> 01:16:04,392
Ahoy, there.

1165
01:16:06,103 --> 01:16:07,687
Ahoy.

1166
01:16:16,863 --> 01:16:19,198
- Been waiting long?
- It's not how long you wait.

1167
01:16:19,366 --> 01:16:20,491
It's who you're waiting for.

1168
01:16:20,659 --> 01:16:23,160
Thank you. And thank you
for the flowers.

1169
01:16:23,328 --> 01:16:25,204
I wanted them to fly orchids
from our greenhouse,

1170
01:16:25,372 --> 01:16:28,249
but unfortunately all
of Long Island is fogged in.

1171
01:16:28,417 --> 01:16:30,084
It's the thought that counts.

1172
01:16:37,134 --> 01:16:39,427
Hm... I seem to be out of gas.

1173
01:16:39,595 --> 01:16:42,847
It's sort of funny, you being out of
gas. I mean, Shell Oil and everything.

1174
01:16:43,015 --> 01:16:45,850
- Hm-hm.... Oops! There.
- [motor starts]

1175
01:16:50,355 --> 01:16:53,274
Uh, it seems to be stuck in reverse.

1176
01:16:53,942 --> 01:16:58,029
Uh... I just got this motorboat.
It's an experimental model.

1177
01:16:58,196 --> 01:17:00,197
It seems like they're
on the wrong track.

1178
01:17:00,365 --> 01:17:03,159
Do you mind riding backwards?
It may take a little longer.

1179
01:17:03,327 --> 01:17:05,786
It's not how long it takes.
It's who's taking you.

1180
01:17:05,954 --> 01:17:07,371
Hm, yes.

1181
01:17:33,231 --> 01:17:35,232
It looked so small from the beach.

1182
01:17:35,400 --> 01:17:38,402
But when you're on it,
it's like a cruiser or a destroyer.

1183
01:17:38,570 --> 01:17:40,905
It's just regulation-size.
We have three like this.

1184
01:17:41,073 --> 01:17:43,449
- Three?
- Yes. Mother keeps hers in Southampton.

1185
01:17:43,617 --> 01:17:46,702
Daddy's is in Venezuela.
The company is laying a new pipeline.

1186
01:17:46,870 --> 01:17:49,413
My dad's more interested in railroads.
Baltimore and Ohio.

1187
01:17:49,581 --> 01:17:50,998
Hm.

1188
01:17:51,166 --> 01:17:53,084
Which is the port
and which is the starboard?

1189
01:17:53,251 --> 01:17:56,087
That depends on
whether you're coming or going.

1190
01:17:56,254 --> 01:17:59,924
I mean, normally the aft
is on the other side of the stern.

1191
01:18:00,717 --> 01:18:01,634
And that's the bridge.

1192
01:18:01,802 --> 01:18:05,054
So that you can get from
one side of the boat to the other.

1193
01:18:05,222 --> 01:18:09,183
- Would you like a glass of champagne?
- Love it. Which way?

1194
01:18:10,894 --> 01:18:13,437
[gasps]
You have an upstairs and a downstairs.

1195
01:18:13,605 --> 01:18:15,773
Yes, the hurricane cellar.

1196
01:18:17,776 --> 01:18:21,445
Uh, and another nice thing about
this yacht - lots of closet space.

1197
01:18:22,364 --> 01:18:26,575
Now, let me see. Where do you
suppose the steward set it up?

1198
01:18:29,371 --> 01:18:31,080
In here.

1199
01:18:32,874 --> 01:18:34,375
Oh, yes, of course. How silly of me.

1200
01:18:34,543 --> 01:18:37,420
On Thursdays they always
serve me in the small salon.

1201
01:18:46,638 --> 01:18:49,932
It's exquisite. Like a floating mansion.

1202
01:18:50,100 --> 01:18:52,435
Uh... It's all right for a bachelor.

1203
01:18:52,978 --> 01:18:56,856
- What a beautiful fish.
- I caught him off Cape Hatteras.

1204
01:18:57,607 --> 01:18:59,150
What is it?

1205
01:18:59,943 --> 01:19:02,319
It's a member of the herring family.

1206
01:19:03,405 --> 01:19:05,322
A herring?

1207
01:19:05,490 --> 01:19:10,369
Isn't it amazing how they get those
big fish into those little glass jars?

1208
01:19:10,537 --> 01:19:12,496
They shrink when they're marinated.

1209
01:19:12,664 --> 01:19:14,707
- Champagne?
- I don't mind if I do.

1210
01:19:14,875 --> 01:19:17,543
Well, down the hatch, as we say at sea.

1211
01:19:17,711 --> 01:19:19,670
Bon voyage.

1212
01:19:23,759 --> 01:19:26,635
- Look at all that silverware.
- Uh... trophies.

1213
01:19:26,803 --> 01:19:30,306
You know. Skeet shooting,
dog breeding, water polo.

1214
01:19:30,474 --> 01:19:32,308
Isn't water polo terribly dangerous?

1215
01:19:32,476 --> 01:19:35,269
I'll say. I had two ponies
drowned under me.

1216
01:19:35,437 --> 01:19:37,313
- Where's your shell collection?
- Hm...

1217
01:19:37,481 --> 01:19:39,857
Yes, of course.
Where could they have put it?

1218
01:19:40,025 --> 01:19:42,485
You see, on Thursdays
I'm sort of lost around here.

1219
01:19:42,652 --> 01:19:45,362
- What's on Thursdays?
- It's the crew's night off.

1220
01:19:45,864 --> 01:19:49,325
- You mean we're alone on the boat?
- Completely.

1221
01:19:49,493 --> 01:19:52,953
I've never been completely alone
with a man in the middle of the night,

1222
01:19:53,121 --> 01:19:55,873
- in the middle of the ocean.
- Oh, it's perfectly safe.

1223
01:19:56,041 --> 01:19:58,751
We're well-anchored.
The ship's in shipshape shape.

1224
01:19:58,919 --> 01:20:01,879
The coastguard promised to call me
if there were any icebergs around.

1225
01:20:02,047 --> 01:20:03,589
It's not the icebergs.

1226
01:20:03,757 --> 01:20:07,134
But certain men would try to
take advantage of a situation like this.

1227
01:20:07,302 --> 01:20:09,720
You're flattering me.

1228
01:20:09,888 --> 01:20:11,347
Of course,
I'm sure you're a gentleman.

1229
01:20:11,515 --> 01:20:15,684
Oh, it's not that.
It's just that I'm... um... harmless.

1230
01:20:15,852 --> 01:20:18,479
- Harmless? How?
- I don't know how to put it,

1231
01:20:18,647 --> 01:20:20,731
but I've got this thing about girls.

1232
01:20:20,899 --> 01:20:24,652
- What thing?
- They just sort of leave me cold.

1233
01:20:24,820 --> 01:20:26,070
You mean, like, frigid?

1234
01:20:27,072 --> 01:20:29,740
Well, it's more like a mental block.

1235
01:20:29,908 --> 01:20:32,451
When I'm with a girl,
it does absolutely nothing to me.

1236
01:20:32,619 --> 01:20:37,289
- Have you tried?
- Have I. I'm trying all the time.

1237
01:20:44,256 --> 01:20:46,966
See? Nothing.

1238
01:20:47,133 --> 01:20:49,718
- Nothing at all?
- Complete washout.

1239
01:20:49,886 --> 01:20:53,097
- That makes me feel just awful.
- Oh, my dear, it's not your fault.

1240
01:20:53,265 --> 01:20:56,141
Just that every now and then Mother
Nature throws somebody a dirty curve.

1241
01:20:56,309 --> 01:20:58,686
Something goes wrong inside.

1242
01:20:58,854 --> 01:21:01,438
- You mean you can't fall in love?
- Not anymore.

1243
01:21:01,606 --> 01:21:04,441
I was in love once,
but I'd rather not talk about it.

1244
01:21:04,609 --> 01:21:07,820
- Would you like a little cold pheasant?
- What happened?

1245
01:21:07,988 --> 01:21:11,240
- I don't want to bore you.
- Oh, you couldn't possibly.

1246
01:21:11,408 --> 01:21:13,409
Well...

1247
01:21:13,577 --> 01:21:15,744
It was my freshman year at Princeton.

1248
01:21:15,912 --> 01:21:18,205
There was this girl.
Her name was Nellie.

1249
01:21:18,373 --> 01:21:21,041
Her father was
the vice president of Hupmobile.

1250
01:21:21,209 --> 01:21:22,960
She wore glasses, too.

1251
01:21:23,795 --> 01:21:26,297
That summer we were
at the Grand Canyon.

1252
01:21:26,464 --> 01:21:29,300
We were on the highest ledge
watching the sunset,

1253
01:21:29,467 --> 01:21:31,927
when suddenly we got
this impulse to kiss.

1254
01:21:32,095 --> 01:21:35,472
I took off my glasses.
She took off her glasses.

1255
01:21:35,640 --> 01:21:37,141
I took a step toward her.

1256
01:21:37,309 --> 01:21:40,895
- She took a step toward me.
- Oh, no!

1257
01:21:41,313 --> 01:21:45,274
Yes. Eight hours later
they brought her up by mule.

1258
01:21:45,442 --> 01:21:49,486
I gave her three transfusions.
We had the same type blood - type O.

1259
01:21:49,654 --> 01:21:51,280
But it was too late.

1260
01:21:52,407 --> 01:21:54,491
Talk about sad.

1261
01:21:54,659 --> 01:21:56,660
Ever since then,

1262
01:21:56,828 --> 01:22:00,331
numb, no feelings, like my heart
was shot full of Novocain.

1263
01:22:00,498 --> 01:22:02,833
You poor, poor boy.

1264
01:22:03,001 --> 01:22:05,836
Yes. All the money in the world,
and what good is it?

1265
01:22:06,004 --> 01:22:07,838
Mint sauce or cranberries?

1266
01:22:08,590 --> 01:22:11,675
How can you think about food
at a time like this?

1267
01:22:11,843 --> 01:22:13,844
What else is there for me?

1268
01:22:14,012 --> 01:22:17,348
- Is it that hopeless?
- My family did everything they could.

1269
01:22:17,515 --> 01:22:20,184
Hired the most beautiful
French upstairs maids.

1270
01:22:20,352 --> 01:22:23,479
Got a special tutor to read me
books that were banned in Boston.

1271
01:22:23,647 --> 01:22:25,898
Imported a troupe of Balinese dancers

1272
01:22:26,066 --> 01:22:29,360
with those bells on their ankles
and long fingernails.

1273
01:22:29,527 --> 01:22:31,528
What a waste of money.

1274
01:22:32,489 --> 01:22:34,323
Have you ever tried American girls?

1275
01:22:34,491 --> 01:22:35,699
Why?

1276
01:22:41,873 --> 01:22:43,582
Was that anything?

1277
01:22:45,418 --> 01:22:47,127
Thanks just the same.

1278
01:22:47,963 --> 01:22:50,047
You should see a doctor - a good doctor.

1279
01:22:50,215 --> 01:22:56,095
I have. I spent six months in Vienna
with Professor Freud, flat on my back.

1280
01:22:56,262 --> 01:23:00,975
Then there were the Mayo brothers,
injections, hypnosis, mineral baths.

1281
01:23:01,142 --> 01:23:03,727
If I wasn't such a coward,
I'd kill myself.

1282
01:23:04,896 --> 01:23:07,064
Don't say that.

1283
01:23:07,232 --> 01:23:09,817
There must be some girl
someplace that could...

1284
01:23:09,985 --> 01:23:14,571
If I ever found a girl that could,
I'd marry her just like that.

1285
01:23:15,407 --> 01:23:17,992
- Would you do me a favor?
- Certainly. What is it?

1286
01:23:18,159 --> 01:23:21,912
I may not be Dr. Freud or a Mayo brother
or one of those French upstairs girls,

1287
01:23:22,080 --> 01:23:25,207
but could I take another crack at it?

1288
01:23:25,875 --> 01:23:27,710
All right, if you insist.

1289
01:23:41,433 --> 01:23:44,351
- Anything this time?
- I'm afraid not.

1290
01:23:45,603 --> 01:23:49,732
- Terribly sorry.
- Would you like some more champagne?

1291
01:23:51,693 --> 01:23:55,362
Maybe if we had some music.
How do you dim these lights?

1292
01:23:56,448 --> 01:23:59,950
Look, it's terribly sweet of you
to want to help out, but it's no use.

1293
01:24:00,118 --> 01:24:02,745
I think the light switch is over there.

1294
01:24:08,126 --> 01:24:10,085
That's the radio.

1295
01:24:10,253 --> 01:24:13,714
It's like taking someone
to a concert when he's tone-deaf.

1296
01:24:13,882 --> 01:24:14,965
[tuning radio]

1297
01:24:15,133 --> 01:24:17,509
<i>[♪ romantic music plays]</i>

1298
01:24:50,168 --> 01:24:52,795
You're not giving yourself a chance.

1299
01:24:52,962 --> 01:24:55,714
Don't fight it.

1300
01:24:56,299 --> 01:24:58,342
Relaaaaax.

1301
01:25:11,689 --> 01:25:13,857
It's like smoking without inhaling.

1302
01:25:14,025 --> 01:25:16,151
So inhale.

1303
01:25:19,614 --> 01:25:22,366
[♪ band playing Hernando's Hideaway]

1304
01:25:39,217 --> 01:25:40,509
- Daphne...
- Hm?

1305
01:25:40,677 --> 01:25:43,053
- ...you're leading again.
- Sorry.

1306
01:25:48,101 --> 01:25:51,228
<i>[♪ romantic music continues on radio]</i>

1307
01:25:57,360 --> 01:25:59,027
Well?

1308
01:26:00,530 --> 01:26:02,531
I'm not quite sure.

1309
01:26:02,699 --> 01:26:05,075
Would you try it again?

1310
01:26:15,253 --> 01:26:18,547
I got a funny sensation in my toes.

1311
01:26:19,465 --> 01:26:22,593
Like someone was barbecuing them
over a slow flame.

1312
01:26:23,970 --> 01:26:26,805
Let's throw another log on the fire.

1313
01:26:36,316 --> 01:26:38,942
I think you're on the right track.

1314
01:26:39,736 --> 01:26:43,280
I must be. Your glasses
are beginning to steam up.

1315
01:26:46,618 --> 01:26:48,785
<i>[♪ Hernando's Hideaway continues]</i>

1316
01:26:57,629 --> 01:27:00,130
<i>[♪ romantic music continues on radio]</i>

1317
01:27:07,931 --> 01:27:10,474
I never knew it could be like this.

1318
01:27:11,893 --> 01:27:13,852
Thank you.

1319
01:27:14,020 --> 01:27:17,147
They told me I was kaput,
finished, all washed up.

1320
01:27:17,315 --> 01:27:20,984
And here you are, making a chump
out of all those experts.

1321
01:27:21,152 --> 01:27:22,569
[chuckling]

1322
01:27:23,738 --> 01:27:25,989
Mineral baths. Now, really.

1323
01:27:26,157 --> 01:27:29,618
Where did you learn to kiss like that?

1324
01:27:29,786 --> 01:27:33,121
I used to sell kisses for the Milk Fund.

1325
01:27:42,840 --> 01:27:47,886
Tomorrow, remind me to send
a check for $100,000 to the Milk Fund.

1326
01:27:50,640 --> 01:27:53,392
<i>[♪ Hernando's Hideaway continues]</i>

1327
01:28:16,916 --> 01:28:18,375
[all] Olé!

1328
01:28:44,235 --> 01:28:47,738
[drunkenly humming
<i>Hernando's Hideaway]</i>

1329
01:28:53,161 --> 01:28:54,619
Whoops.

1330
01:28:56,414 --> 01:28:58,040
[engine starting]

1331
01:29:22,440 --> 01:29:25,442
- Good night.
- Good morning.

1332
01:29:25,610 --> 01:29:27,694
How much do I owe the Milk Fund so far?

1333
01:29:27,862 --> 01:29:30,405
$850,000.

1334
01:29:30,573 --> 01:29:33,241
Let's make it an even million.

1335
01:29:53,805 --> 01:29:56,640
I forgot to give you a receipt.

1336
01:30:22,333 --> 01:30:25,460
[humming Hernando's Hideaway]

1337
01:30:36,514 --> 01:30:37,556
Olé!

1338
01:30:37,723 --> 01:30:40,058
Hi, Jerry. Everything under control?

1339
01:30:40,226 --> 01:30:42,185
Have I got things to tell you.

1340
01:30:43,020 --> 01:30:46,481
- What happened?
- I'm engaged.

1341
01:30:46,649 --> 01:30:48,733
Congratulations. Who's the lucky girl?

1342
01:30:49,944 --> 01:30:51,111
I am.

1343
01:30:51,279 --> 01:30:53,363
[humming]

1344
01:30:55,867 --> 01:30:56,867
What?

1345
01:30:57,994 --> 01:31:00,704
Osgood proposed to me.
We're planning a June wedding.

1346
01:31:00,872 --> 01:31:03,206
[humming]

1347
01:31:03,916 --> 01:31:06,877
What are you talking about?
You can't marry Osgood.

1348
01:31:08,004 --> 01:31:11,673
- Do you think he's too old for me?
- Jerry, you can't be serious.

1349
01:31:11,841 --> 01:31:14,634
Why not? He keeps
marryin' girls all the time.

1350
01:31:16,053 --> 01:31:18,096
But... But you're not a girl.
You're a guy.

1351
01:31:18,264 --> 01:31:20,265
And why would a guy
wanna marry a guy?

1352
01:31:20,433 --> 01:31:22,100
Security.

1353
01:31:23,436 --> 01:31:26,897
- Jerry, lie down. You're not well.
- Stop treatin' me like a child.

1354
01:31:27,064 --> 01:31:28,982
I'm not stupid.
I know there's a problem.

1355
01:31:29,150 --> 01:31:30,942
- I'll say there is.
- His mother.

1356
01:31:31,110 --> 01:31:35,197
We need her approval. But I'm not
worried because I don't smoke.

1357
01:31:38,034 --> 01:31:41,495
- Jerry, there's another problem.
- Like what?

1358
01:31:41,662 --> 01:31:45,582
- Like your honeymoon.
- We've been discussing that.

1359
01:31:45,750 --> 01:31:49,920
He wants to go to the Riviera,
but I kinda lean towards Niagara Falls.

1360
01:31:53,591 --> 01:31:56,718
Jerry, you're outta your mind.
How are you gonna get away with this?

1361
01:31:56,886 --> 01:32:00,764
I don't expect it to last. I'll tell him
the truth when the time comes.

1362
01:32:00,932 --> 01:32:03,642
- Like when?
- Like right after the ceremony.

1363
01:32:03,809 --> 01:32:07,229
Then we get a quick annulment,
he makes a nice settlement on me

1364
01:32:07,396 --> 01:32:10,607
and I keep gettin' those
alimony checks every month.

1365
01:32:14,028 --> 01:32:16,947
Jerry... Jerry, listen to me.

1366
01:32:17,114 --> 01:32:20,492
There are laws, conventions.
It's just not been done.

1367
01:32:20,660 --> 01:32:24,287
Shh! Joe, this may be my last chance
to marry a millionaire.

1368
01:32:24,455 --> 01:32:28,458
Jerry, will you take my advice?
Forget about the whole thing, will you?

1369
01:32:28,626 --> 01:32:32,337
Just keep telling yourself you're a boy.
You're a boy.

1370
01:32:32,505 --> 01:32:35,632
- I'm a boy.
- That's the boy.

1371
01:32:35,800 --> 01:32:38,468
Oh, I'm a boy, I'm a boy, I'm a...

1372
01:32:38,636 --> 01:32:43,223
[sighs] I wish I were dead.
I'm a boy. Boy, oh boy, am I a boy.

1373
01:32:43,391 --> 01:32:45,684
What am I gonna do
about my engagement present?

1374
01:32:45,851 --> 01:32:49,396
- What engagement present?
- Osgood gave me a bracelet.

1375
01:32:51,107 --> 01:32:52,691
Hey, these are real diamonds.

1376
01:32:52,858 --> 01:32:55,527
Of course they're real.
You think my fiancé is a bum?

1377
01:32:55,695 --> 01:32:57,487
I guess I'll have
to give it back to him.

1378
01:32:57,655 --> 01:32:59,990
Wait a minute, Jerry.
Let's not be hasty.

1379
01:33:00,157 --> 01:33:02,659
After all, we don't wanna
hurt Osgood's feelings.

1380
01:33:02,827 --> 01:33:05,495
- Huh?
- [knock on door]

1381
01:33:06,831 --> 01:33:09,666
- [as Josephine] Just a minute.
- It's me. Sugar.

1382
01:33:16,841 --> 01:33:17,841
Come in.

1383
01:33:19,093 --> 01:33:22,220
I thought I heard voices.
I had to talk to somebody.

1384
01:33:22,388 --> 01:33:23,930
I don't feel like going to sleep.

1385
01:33:24,098 --> 01:33:27,851
- What you need is a slug of bourbon.
- Oh, no. I'm off that stuff for good.

1386
01:33:28,436 --> 01:33:31,229
- Did you have a nice time?
- Nice?

1387
01:33:32,064 --> 01:33:35,025
It was suicidally beautiful.

1388
01:33:35,192 --> 01:33:36,192
Did he get fresh?

1389
01:33:36,360 --> 01:33:39,613
Of course not. As a matter of fact,
it was just the other way around.

1390
01:33:39,780 --> 01:33:42,449
- You see, he needs help.
- What for?

1391
01:33:42,617 --> 01:33:45,368
Talk about elegant.
You should see the yacht.

1392
01:33:45,536 --> 01:33:49,039
Candlelight, mint sauce and cranberries.

1393
01:33:49,206 --> 01:33:51,416
Gee, I wish I'd been there.

1394
01:33:51,584 --> 01:33:54,586
I'm going to see him again
tonight - and every night.

1395
01:33:54,754 --> 01:33:56,212
I think he's going to propose.

1396
01:33:56,380 --> 01:33:59,341
- As soon as he gets up his nerve.
- That's some nerve.

1397
01:33:59,508 --> 01:34:01,718
Daphne got a proposal tonight.

1398
01:34:02,428 --> 01:34:04,721
- Really?
- From a rich millionaire.

1399
01:34:04,889 --> 01:34:06,514
That's wonderful.

1400
01:34:06,682 --> 01:34:08,933
- Poor Josephine.
- Me?

1401
01:34:09,101 --> 01:34:10,852
Well, Daphne has a beau,
I have a beau...

1402
01:34:11,020 --> 01:34:13,521
If we could only find somebody for you.

1403
01:34:16,400 --> 01:34:18,276
Here I am, doll.

1404
01:34:20,863 --> 01:34:22,530
Ohhhh...

1405
01:34:40,800 --> 01:34:42,217
Hey!

1406
01:34:44,095 --> 01:34:47,639
"Friends of Italian Opera" - that's us.

1407
01:34:48,099 --> 01:34:49,933
Register over there.

1408
01:34:59,151 --> 01:35:02,696
Spats Colombo. Delegate from Chicago.
South Side Chapter.

1409
01:35:03,614 --> 01:35:05,031
Thanks.

1410
01:35:05,866 --> 01:35:07,325
Hiya, Spats.

1411
01:35:07,493 --> 01:35:10,578
- We was layin' 8-1 you wouldn't show.
- Why wouldn't I?

1412
01:35:10,746 --> 01:35:13,873
We thought you was all broken up
about Toothpick Charlie.

1413
01:35:14,041 --> 01:35:18,294
- We all gotta go sometime.
- Yeah. You never know who's next.

1414
01:35:18,462 --> 01:35:20,797
OK, Spats.
Report to the sergeant at arms.

1415
01:35:20,965 --> 01:35:24,634
- What for?
- Orders from Little Bonaparte.

1416
01:35:29,473 --> 01:35:32,225
- All right, Spats, get your hands up.
- What's the idea?

1417
01:35:32,393 --> 01:35:34,769
Little Bonaparte don't want
no hardware around.

1418
01:35:35,479 --> 01:35:37,147
All right, you're clean.

1419
01:35:37,815 --> 01:35:39,941
You're not.

1420
01:35:50,161 --> 01:35:51,953
It ain't loaded.

1421
01:36:00,463 --> 01:36:03,339
Next. What's in here?

1422
01:36:03,507 --> 01:36:07,469
My golf clubs.
Putter, niblick, No.3 iron.

1423
01:36:07,887 --> 01:36:10,346
- What's this?
- My mashie.

1424
01:36:15,352 --> 01:36:17,187
See you at the banquet, Spats.

1425
01:36:18,814 --> 01:36:21,316
Where did you pick up that cheap trick?

1426
01:36:22,193 --> 01:36:23,902
Come on, boys.

1427
01:36:25,404 --> 01:36:27,655
Well. Spats Colombo, if I ever saw one.

1428
01:36:27,823 --> 01:36:30,033
Hello, copper.
What brings you to Florida?

1429
01:36:30,201 --> 01:36:32,243
I heard you opera-lovers
were having a little rally.

1430
01:36:32,411 --> 01:36:35,371
Thought I'd better be around
in case anybody decided to sing.

1431
01:36:35,539 --> 01:36:36,706
Big joke.

1432
01:36:36,874 --> 01:36:39,209
Where were you at 3pm
on St. Valentine's Day?

1433
01:36:39,376 --> 01:36:42,378
- Me? I was at Rigoletto.
- What's his first name and address?

1434
01:36:42,546 --> 01:36:44,547
- It's an opera, you ignoramus.
- Where'd they play it?

1435
01:36:44,715 --> 01:36:47,926
- In the garage on Clark Street?
- Clark Street? Never heard of it.

1436
01:36:48,093 --> 01:36:50,804
Ever hear of Deluxe Cleaners
on Wabash Avenue?

1437
01:36:50,971 --> 01:36:51,888
Why?

1438
01:36:52,056 --> 01:36:54,933
The day after the shoot
you sent in spats with blood on 'em.

1439
01:36:55,100 --> 01:36:56,893
I cut myself while shaving.

1440
01:36:57,061 --> 01:36:59,729
- You shave with spats on?
- I sleep with my spats on.

1441
01:36:59,897 --> 01:37:03,233
Stop kidding. You vulcanized
Toothpick Charlie, and we know it.

1442
01:37:03,400 --> 01:37:04,692
You and who else?

1443
01:37:04,860 --> 01:37:08,738
Me and those two witnesses your lawyers
have been lookin' for all over Chicago.

1444
01:37:08,906 --> 01:37:11,741
Boys, know anything about
any garage or witnesses?

1445
01:37:11,909 --> 01:37:14,536
Us? We was with you at Rigoletto's.

1446
01:37:14,703 --> 01:37:16,579
Honest.

1447
01:37:18,499 --> 01:37:22,752
Don't worry, Spats. One of these days
we're gonna dig up those two guys.

1448
01:37:22,920 --> 01:37:25,421
That's what you'll have to do -
dig 'em up.

1449
01:37:34,974 --> 01:37:36,683
I feel like such a tramp,

1450
01:37:36,851 --> 01:37:39,227
taking jewelry from a man
under false pretences.

1451
01:37:39,395 --> 01:37:43,189
Get it while you're young. Fix your lips
if you wanna look nice for Osgood.

1452
01:37:43,357 --> 01:37:45,775
It'll break his heart when
he finds out I can't marry him.

1453
01:37:45,943 --> 01:37:48,444
It'll break Sugar's heart when
she finds out I'm not a millionaire.

1454
01:37:48,612 --> 01:37:51,614
That's life. Can't make an omelet
without breakin' an egg.

1455
01:37:51,782 --> 01:37:54,158
- What's with the omelet?
- Nag, nag, nag.

1456
01:37:54,326 --> 01:37:57,912
Look, we got a yacht, a bracelet,
you've got Osgood, I've got Sugar.

1457
01:37:58,080 --> 01:37:59,622
We're really cookin'.

1458
01:38:03,460 --> 01:38:05,587
- Joe!
- What?

1459
01:38:06,964 --> 01:38:10,008
Something tells me the omelet
is about to hit the fan.

1460
01:38:12,887 --> 01:38:14,387
- Come on, Daphne.
- Mm-hm!

1461
01:38:19,143 --> 01:38:20,852
- Going up.
- [Spats] Hold it.

1462
01:38:29,236 --> 01:38:30,486
Three, please.

1463
01:38:42,207 --> 01:38:43,583
I don't mean to be forward,

1464
01:38:43,751 --> 01:38:46,711
but ain't I had the pleasure
of meetin' you two broads before?

1465
01:38:46,879 --> 01:38:50,048
- Oh, no.
- You must mean two other broads.

1466
01:38:50,215 --> 01:38:52,926
- You ever been in Chicago?
- Us?

1467
01:38:53,093 --> 01:38:55,678
We wouldn't be caught dead in Chicago.

1468
01:38:55,846 --> 01:38:56,846
[operator] Third floor.

1469
01:38:57,014 --> 01:39:00,850
- What floor are you on, sweetie?
- Never you mind.

1470
01:39:01,602 --> 01:39:03,394
Room 413. We'll be in touch.

1471
01:39:03,562 --> 01:39:06,147
Don't call us. We'll call you.
[nervous chuckle]

1472
01:39:11,570 --> 01:39:13,196
[groaning]

1473
01:39:18,994 --> 01:39:20,620
I tell you, Joe, they're onto us.

1474
01:39:20,788 --> 01:39:24,040
They're gonna line us up against
the wall and... [imitates gunfire]

1475
01:39:24,208 --> 01:39:27,460
The cops will find two dead dames
and take us to the ladies' morgue

1476
01:39:27,628 --> 01:39:30,046
and when they undress us,
I'm gonna die of shame.

1477
01:39:30,214 --> 01:39:33,132
- Shut up and keep packing.
- Yeah. OK, Joe.

1478
01:39:33,300 --> 01:39:35,385
- Not that, you idiot.
- They're from Osgood.

1479
01:39:35,552 --> 01:39:37,303
He wanted me to wear 'em tonight.

1480
01:39:38,722 --> 01:39:40,765
[humming Hernando's Hideaway]

1481
01:39:41,809 --> 01:39:44,560
I tell you, I will never find
another man who's so good to me.

1482
01:39:44,728 --> 01:39:47,146
Joe, if we get outta this hotel alive,
you know what we're gonna do?

1483
01:39:47,314 --> 01:39:49,232
We're gonna sell this bracelet,
take the money,

1484
01:39:49,400 --> 01:39:52,443
grab a boat to South America
and hide out in a banana republic.

1485
01:39:52,611 --> 01:39:55,530
I figured if we eat nothing but bananas,
we could live there for 50 years.

1486
01:39:55,698 --> 01:39:58,366
Maybe 100 years.
If we get outta the hotel alive.

1487
01:39:58,534 --> 01:40:01,160
- Did we forget anything?
- Yeah. The shaving stuff.

1488
01:40:01,328 --> 01:40:02,870
- Oh, yeah.
- And also Sugar.

1489
01:40:03,038 --> 01:40:03,997
Sugar?

1490
01:40:04,164 --> 01:40:05,999
- Give me room 414.
- What are you doin'?

1491
01:40:06,166 --> 01:40:08,543
- Making a telephone call.
- Who has time?

1492
01:40:08,711 --> 01:40:11,212
We can't walk out on her
without saying goodbye.

1493
01:40:11,380 --> 01:40:13,923
Since when? You usually walk out and
leave 'em with a kick in the teeth.

1494
01:40:14,091 --> 01:40:17,510
That's when I was a saxophone player.
Now I'm a millionaire.

1495
01:40:17,678 --> 01:40:20,763
Mail her a postcard.
Those gorillas may be here any minute.

1496
01:40:20,931 --> 01:40:24,225
[mimics female operator] Hello, room
414? This is the ship-to-shore operator.

1497
01:40:24,393 --> 01:40:25,435
Ship to shore?

1498
01:40:25,936 --> 01:40:28,438
Hey, Sugar, it's for you.
From the yacht.

1499
01:40:30,691 --> 01:40:31,691
Hello?

1500
01:40:33,527 --> 01:40:37,155
[as Junior] Hello, my dearest darling.
It's so good to hear your voice.

1501
01:40:37,322 --> 01:40:39,240
[whispers] I may throw up.

1502
01:40:41,368 --> 01:40:43,453
No, I didn't sleep too well, darling.

1503
01:40:43,620 --> 01:40:45,455
To tell the truth,
I never closed an eye.

1504
01:40:45,622 --> 01:40:49,208
I never slept better.
I had the most wonderful dream.

1505
01:40:49,376 --> 01:40:51,794
I was still on the yacht
and the anchor broke loose.

1506
01:40:51,962 --> 01:40:54,422
We drifted for days and days.

1507
01:40:54,590 --> 01:40:56,632
You were the captain and I was the crew.

1508
01:40:56,800 --> 01:41:01,679
I kept a lookout for icebergs, I sorted
your shells and mixed your cocktails,

1509
01:41:01,847 --> 01:41:04,640
and I wiped the steam off your glasses.

1510
01:41:04,808 --> 01:41:08,811
And when I woke up, I wanted
to swim right back to you.

1511
01:41:09,396 --> 01:41:10,855
Yes...

1512
01:41:11,565 --> 01:41:13,816
Now, about our date for tonight. Uh...

1513
01:41:13,984 --> 01:41:16,944
I'll meet you on the pier again
right after the show.

1514
01:41:17,821 --> 01:41:21,157
I'm afraid not. I can't make it tonight.

1515
01:41:22,826 --> 01:41:25,119
Not tomorrow either. I have to leave.

1516
01:41:25,287 --> 01:41:28,247
Something unexpected came up.
I'm sailing right away.

1517
01:41:29,166 --> 01:41:30,750
Where to?

1518
01:41:31,502 --> 01:41:33,377
South America?

1519
01:41:33,545 --> 01:41:34,796
Oh.

1520
01:41:34,963 --> 01:41:37,048
That is unexpected.

1521
01:41:38,092 --> 01:41:40,843
You see, we have
these oil interests in Venezuela.

1522
01:41:41,011 --> 01:41:45,014
I just got a cable from Dad. The board
of directors have decided on a merger.

1523
01:41:45,182 --> 01:41:48,184
A merger? How long will you be gone?

1524
01:41:50,354 --> 01:41:52,188
Quite a while.

1525
01:41:52,356 --> 01:41:54,482
As a matter of fact,
I'm not coming back at all.

1526
01:41:55,192 --> 01:41:56,192
You're not?

1527
01:41:57,903 --> 01:42:01,197
Well, it's all rather complicated.
What we call high finance.

1528
01:42:01,365 --> 01:42:04,367
It just so happens the president
of the Venezuelan oil syndicate

1529
01:42:04,535 --> 01:42:06,160
has a daughter and, uh...

1530
01:42:06,328 --> 01:42:09,247
Oh. That kind of merger.

1531
01:42:09,540 --> 01:42:10,665
What is she like?

1532
01:42:11,458 --> 01:42:14,127
According to our tax adviser,
she's only so-so.

1533
01:42:14,294 --> 01:42:16,337
But that's the way the oil gushes.

1534
01:42:16,505 --> 01:42:19,882
A man in my position has a certain
responsibility to the stockholders.

1535
01:42:20,050 --> 01:42:23,177
You know, all those little people
who have invested their life savings.

1536
01:42:23,887 --> 01:42:27,890
Of course. I understand.
At least, I think I do.

1537
01:42:28,058 --> 01:42:33,938
I knew you would. I only wish there
was something I could do for you.

1538
01:42:34,106 --> 01:42:37,692
But you have. You've given me
all that inside information.

1539
01:42:37,860 --> 01:42:39,569
Tomorrow I'm gonna call my broker

1540
01:42:39,736 --> 01:42:43,072
and have him buy me
50,000 shares of Venezuelan oil.

1541
01:42:43,240 --> 01:42:45,074
Smart move.

1542
01:42:45,450 --> 01:42:48,369
By the way, did you get my flowers?

1543
01:42:48,537 --> 01:42:50,913
You know, those orchids
from my greenhouse?

1544
01:42:51,081 --> 01:42:55,251
The fog finally lifted over Long Island
and they flew them down this morning.

1545
01:42:55,419 --> 01:42:59,255
That's strange. I sent 'em to your room.

1546
01:43:00,924 --> 01:43:03,342
They should have been delivered by now.

1547
01:43:06,972 --> 01:43:09,932
Hey, Dolores, will you see
if there's any flowers outside?

1548
01:43:16,481 --> 01:43:19,233
Yes, they're here. White orchids.

1549
01:43:19,401 --> 01:43:22,486
I haven't had white orchids
since I was a debutante.

1550
01:43:24,364 --> 01:43:26,449
What's this?

1551
01:43:27,492 --> 01:43:28,951
What's what?

1552
01:43:29,119 --> 01:43:31,829
Oh, that.
Just a little going-away present.

1553
01:43:32,623 --> 01:43:35,458
Real diamonds.

1554
01:43:35,626 --> 01:43:40,213
They must be worth their weight in gold.
Are you always this generous?

1555
01:43:41,506 --> 01:43:43,090
Not always.

1556
01:43:43,258 --> 01:43:46,260
I wanted you to know how grateful
I am for what you did for me.

1557
01:43:46,428 --> 01:43:49,722
I didn't do anything. It just happened.

1558
01:43:51,350 --> 01:43:55,269
Oh! The navigator just came in.
We're ready to cast off.

1559
01:43:55,437 --> 01:43:58,648
Well, anchors aweigh,
and have a bon voyage.

1560
01:43:58,815 --> 01:44:01,234
If you need an orchestra
to play at your wedding,

1561
01:44:01,401 --> 01:44:03,444
we'll be through here
in a couple of weeks.

1562
01:44:03,612 --> 01:44:05,988
- Goodbye, my darling.
- [sighs]

1563
01:44:06,156 --> 01:44:09,492
I don't know about the captain but the
navigator's gettin' his tail outta here.

1564
01:44:09,660 --> 01:44:12,328
- Yeah, let's shove off.
- Wait a minute. My bracelet.

1565
01:44:15,415 --> 01:44:17,124
What happened to my bracelet?

1566
01:44:17,292 --> 01:44:19,168
Your bracelet? It's our bracelet.

1567
01:44:19,336 --> 01:44:21,128
All right.
What happened to our bracelet?

1568
01:44:21,296 --> 01:44:22,713
Don't worry.
We did the right thing with it.

1569
01:44:22,881 --> 01:44:25,758
What did we do? You're not
pullin' one of your old tricks.

1570
01:44:25,926 --> 01:44:28,219
No tricks, no mirrors,
nothing up my sleeve.

1571
01:44:28,387 --> 01:44:29,679
It's on the level this time.

1572
01:44:29,846 --> 01:44:31,138
- You...
- [door opens]

1573
01:44:37,020 --> 01:44:39,188
[tearfully] Where's that bourbon?

1574
01:44:45,112 --> 01:44:46,237
What's the matter, Sugar?

1575
01:44:46,405 --> 01:44:49,991
I don't know.
All of a sudden I'm thirsty.

1576
01:44:51,034 --> 01:44:52,868
How did you get that bracelet?

1577
01:44:53,036 --> 01:44:54,870
- You like it?
- I always did.

1578
01:44:55,038 --> 01:44:59,875
Junior gave it to me. He's going
to South America to marry another girl.

1579
01:45:00,043 --> 01:45:02,878
- That's what you call high finance.
- That's what I call a louse.

1580
01:45:03,046 --> 01:45:06,882
If I were you, I'd take that bracelet
and throw it back in his face.

1581
01:45:07,050 --> 01:45:08,718
- Daphne...
- He's the first nice guy

1582
01:45:08,885 --> 01:45:11,512
I've ever met in my life. The only one
that ever gave me anything.

1583
01:45:11,680 --> 01:45:13,472
You'll forget him, Sugar.

1584
01:45:14,975 --> 01:45:16,267
How can I?

1585
01:45:16,435 --> 01:45:20,313
No matter where I go, there'll always
be a Shell station on every corner.

1586
01:45:20,480 --> 01:45:22,565
I'll bring this back when it's empty.

1587
01:45:25,736 --> 01:45:28,821
Are you crazy?
The place is crawlin' with mobsters.

1588
01:45:28,989 --> 01:45:32,408
Gangrene is settin' in and
you're makin' like Diamond Jim Brady.

1589
01:45:32,576 --> 01:45:34,702
How are we gonna get outta here?
How are we gonna eat?

1590
01:45:34,870 --> 01:45:36,245
We'll walk.
If we have to, we'll starve.

1591
01:45:36,413 --> 01:45:38,414
There you go with that "we" again.

1592
01:45:38,582 --> 01:45:41,542
Not that way. We don't wanna
run into Spats and his chums.

1593
01:45:41,710 --> 01:45:43,002
Oh.

1594
01:45:51,428 --> 01:45:53,262
Your hands clean?

1595
01:45:53,430 --> 01:45:54,555
Over.

1596
01:45:54,723 --> 01:45:56,432
OK, button my spats.

1597
01:46:00,145 --> 01:46:01,937
You sure dress nice, boss.

1598
01:46:02,105 --> 01:46:05,358
Say, boss. I've been talking
with the other delegates.

1599
01:46:05,525 --> 01:46:07,818
The word is, Little Bonaparte
is real sore about

1600
01:46:07,986 --> 01:46:11,906
what happened to Toothpick Charlie.
Him and Charlie was choirboys together.

1601
01:46:12,074 --> 01:46:13,741
Stop or I'll bust out cryin'.

1602
01:46:13,909 --> 01:46:17,453
He even got Charlie's last toothpick
from the garage. Had it gold-plated.

1603
01:46:17,621 --> 01:46:19,372
Like I was tellin' you fellas.

1604
01:46:19,539 --> 01:46:22,875
Little Bonaparte's gettin' soft.
Hasn't got it here anymore.

1605
01:46:23,043 --> 01:46:25,461
Used to be like a rock.

1606
01:46:25,629 --> 01:46:29,256
It's too bad.
I think it's time he retired.

1607
01:46:29,424 --> 01:46:30,466
Second the motion.

1608
01:46:30,634 --> 01:46:32,468
How are we gonna retire him?

1609
01:46:32,636 --> 01:46:34,303
Oh, we'll think of somethin' cute.

1610
01:46:34,471 --> 01:46:36,555
One of these days, Little Bonaparte
and Toothpick Charlie

1611
01:46:36,723 --> 01:46:39,016
will be singin' in the same choir again.

1612
01:46:39,559 --> 01:46:41,185
[thud]

1613
01:46:42,229 --> 01:46:45,272
[Spats] But this time we'll make sure
there are no witnesses.

1614
01:46:48,193 --> 01:46:51,445
Look. The two broads from the elevator.

1615
01:46:54,658 --> 01:46:57,076
Hey. Join us.

1616
01:46:57,911 --> 01:47:00,538
What's the matter with those dames?

1617
01:47:00,705 --> 01:47:02,665
[Spats] Maybe those dames ain't dames.

1618
01:47:05,669 --> 01:47:07,962
Same faces, same instruments.

1619
01:47:12,175 --> 01:47:15,344
- Here's your Valentine's card.
- The two musicians from the garage.

1620
01:47:15,512 --> 01:47:20,599
They wouldn't be caught dead in Chicago,
so we'll finish the job here. Come on.

1621
01:47:39,202 --> 01:47:41,036
All right, so what do we do now?

1622
01:47:41,204 --> 01:47:43,497
First thing we gotta do
is get out of these clothes.

1623
01:47:52,591 --> 01:47:53,924
Yoo-hoo!

1624
01:49:22,847 --> 01:49:23,764
What happened?

1625
01:49:23,932 --> 01:49:27,309
Me and Tiny had them cornered,
but we lost them in the shuffle.

1626
01:49:27,477 --> 01:49:30,688
- Where were you guys?
- We was with you, at Rigoletto's.

1627
01:49:30,855 --> 01:49:32,106
Why, you stupid idiot.

1628
01:49:32,274 --> 01:49:34,608
That's all right, boss,
we'll get 'em after the banquet.

1629
01:49:34,776 --> 01:49:36,860
They can't be too far away.

1630
01:49:38,363 --> 01:49:40,364
[burst of applause]

1631
01:49:56,381 --> 01:49:58,382
- Thank you.
- [applause dies out]

1632
01:49:58,550 --> 01:50:00,926
Thank you, fellow opera-lovers.

1633
01:50:02,137 --> 01:50:06,098
It's been ten years since I elected
myself president of this organization,

1634
01:50:06,266 --> 01:50:09,268
and, if I say so myself,
you made the right choice.

1635
01:50:09,436 --> 01:50:11,478
[clapping]

1636
01:50:12,188 --> 01:50:15,566
Let's look at the record.
In the last fiscal year,

1637
01:50:15,734 --> 01:50:20,029
we made $112 million before taxes.

1638
01:50:20,196 --> 01:50:21,822
Only we ain't payin' no taxes.

1639
01:50:24,492 --> 01:50:28,704
Of course, like in every business,
we had our little misunderstandings.

1640
01:50:30,665 --> 01:50:32,666
Let us now rise and
observe one minute of silence

1641
01:50:32,834 --> 01:50:37,379
in memory of seven of our members
from Chicago, North Side Chapter,

1642
01:50:37,547 --> 01:50:41,133
who are unable to be with us tonight
on account of bein' rubbed out.

1643
01:50:46,848 --> 01:50:48,390
You too, Spats.

1644
01:50:48,558 --> 01:50:49,850
Up.

1645
01:51:00,445 --> 01:51:01,904
Easy, now.

1646
01:51:02,072 --> 01:51:05,532
- You know when you come out?
- Yeah. Second time they sing:

1647
01:51:05,700 --> 01:51:09,995
<i>♪ For he's a jolly good fellow</i>
<i>which nobody can deny</i>

1648
01:51:10,163 --> 01:51:11,622
OK.

1649
01:51:16,127 --> 01:51:20,339
And don't mess up the cake. I promised
to bring back a piece to my kids.

1650
01:51:28,682 --> 01:51:30,599
Now, fellow delegates,

1651
01:51:30,767 --> 01:51:34,353
there comes a time in the life
of every business executive

1652
01:51:34,521 --> 01:51:37,564
when he starts thinkin'
about retirement.

1653
01:51:37,732 --> 01:51:39,400
[outcry] No!

1654
01:51:41,861 --> 01:51:45,406
I'm lookin' around
for somebody to fill my shoes.

1655
01:51:45,573 --> 01:51:48,283
I've been considerin'
several candidates.

1656
01:51:48,451 --> 01:51:52,162
For instance, there's
a certain party from Chicago,

1657
01:51:52,330 --> 01:51:54,206
South Side Chapter.

1658
01:51:56,292 --> 01:52:01,630
Now, some people say he's gotten
a little too big for his spats.

1659
01:52:01,798 --> 01:52:05,509
But I say he's a man who'll go far.

1660
01:52:05,677 --> 01:52:09,847
Some people say he's gone too far.

1661
01:52:10,014 --> 01:52:14,685
But I say,
you can't keep a good man down.

1662
01:52:14,853 --> 01:52:16,812
Of course,
he's still got a lot to learn.

1663
01:52:16,980 --> 01:52:19,773
The big noise he made
on St. Valentine's Day,

1664
01:52:19,941 --> 01:52:23,235
that wasn't very good
for public relations.

1665
01:52:23,403 --> 01:52:28,282
And lettin' them two witnesses get away,
that sure was careless.

1666
01:52:29,492 --> 01:52:32,369
Don't worry about those two guys.
They're as good as dead.

1667
01:52:32,537 --> 01:52:34,496
I almost caught up with them today.

1668
01:52:34,664 --> 01:52:38,876
You mean you let 'em get away twice?

1669
01:52:39,043 --> 01:52:42,004
Some people would say
that's real sloppy.

1670
01:52:42,172 --> 01:52:46,300
But I say: to err is human,
to forgive divine.

1671
01:52:46,468 --> 01:52:48,844
And just to show you
what I think of you, Spats,

1672
01:52:49,012 --> 01:52:51,513
the boys told me
you was gonna have a birthday.

1673
01:52:51,681 --> 01:52:53,849
So we baked you a little cake.

1674
01:52:54,517 --> 01:52:56,310
My birthday?

1675
01:52:56,478 --> 01:52:58,520
Why, it ain't for another four months.

1676
01:52:59,147 --> 01:53:03,066
So we're a little early.
What's a few months between friends?

1677
01:53:03,234 --> 01:53:05,277
All right, boys. Now all together.

1678
01:53:05,445 --> 01:53:08,197
[all singing]
<i>♪ For he's a jolly good fellow</i>

1679
01:53:08,364 --> 01:53:14,369
<i>♪ For he's a jolly good fellow</i>

1680
01:53:14,537 --> 01:53:22,002
<i>♪ Which nobody can deny</i>

1681
01:53:22,170 --> 01:53:30,385
<i>♪ For he's a jolly good fellow</i>

1682
01:53:30,804 --> 01:53:33,388
<i>♪ Which nobody can deny ♪</i>

1683
01:53:39,062 --> 01:53:41,146
[gunfire continues]

1684
01:53:43,900 --> 01:53:45,275
[grunting]

1685
01:53:49,155 --> 01:53:50,405
Big joke.

1686
01:53:50,573 --> 01:53:52,407
[blast of gunfire]

1687
01:53:58,373 --> 01:54:00,040
[whispers] Let's get outta here.

1688
01:54:03,294 --> 01:54:05,254
Get those two guys.

1689
01:54:05,421 --> 01:54:07,923
[low, indistinct chatter]

1690
01:54:10,468 --> 01:54:12,010
[chatter fades]

1691
01:54:12,595 --> 01:54:14,429
What happened here?

1692
01:54:14,597 --> 01:54:17,850
There was somethin' in that cake
that didn't agree with 'em.

1693
01:54:18,017 --> 01:54:19,434
[scattered laughter]

1694
01:54:20,103 --> 01:54:24,356
My compliments to the chef. Nobody
leaves this room till I get the recipe.

1695
01:54:24,524 --> 01:54:27,109
You wanna make a federal case of it?

1696
01:54:31,489 --> 01:54:32,948
Yeah.

1697
01:55:00,935 --> 01:55:02,603
- They slipped through our hands.
- Don't worry.

1698
01:55:02,770 --> 01:55:06,648
We're watchin' the train station,
roads and airport. They can't get away.

1699
01:55:06,816 --> 01:55:09,735
- Did you hear that?
- Yeah, but they're not watching yachts.

1700
01:55:09,903 --> 01:55:13,196
- Come on. You're gonna call Osgood.
- What'll I tell him?

1701
01:55:13,364 --> 01:55:15,741
- Tell him you're gonna elope with him.
- Elope?

1702
01:55:16,159 --> 01:55:18,827
Elope? But there are laws, conventions.

1703
01:55:18,995 --> 01:55:22,831
There's a convention, all right.
There's also the ladies' morgue.

1704
01:55:26,169 --> 01:55:27,836
[♪ Sugar singing I'm Through With Love]

1705
01:55:28,004 --> 01:55:30,589
<i>♪ I'm through with love</i>

1706
01:55:30,757 --> 01:55:33,300
<i>♪ I'll never fall again</i>

1707
01:55:33,468 --> 01:55:35,677
<i>♪ Said adieu to love</i>

1708
01:55:35,845 --> 01:55:38,430
<i>♪ Don't ever call again</i>

1709
01:55:38,598 --> 01:55:40,766
<i>♪ For I must have you</i>

1710
01:55:40,934 --> 01:55:43,685
<i>♪ Or no one</i>

1711
01:55:43,853 --> 01:55:47,522
<i>♪ And so I'm through with love</i>

1712
01:55:48,691 --> 01:55:50,692
<i>♪ I've locked my heart</i>

1713
01:55:50,860 --> 01:55:53,570
<i>♪ I'll keep my feelings there</i>

1714
01:55:53,738 --> 01:55:58,450
<i>♪ I've stocked my heart with icy,</i>
<i>frigid air</i>

1715
01:55:58,618 --> 01:56:03,622
<i>♪ And I mean to care for no one</i>

1716
01:56:03,790 --> 01:56:07,542
<i>♪ Because I'm through with love</i>

1717
01:56:08,962 --> 01:56:13,507
<i>♪ Why did you lead me</i>
<i>to think you could care?</i>

1718
01:56:13,675 --> 01:56:18,387
<i>♪ You didn't need me, you had your share</i>

1719
01:56:18,554 --> 01:56:23,558
<i>♪ Of slaves around you</i>
<i>to hound you and swear</i>

1720
01:56:23,726 --> 01:56:29,022
<i>♪ With deep emotion, devotion to you</i>

1721
01:56:29,190 --> 01:56:33,527
<i>♪ Goodbye to spring</i>
<i>and all it meant to me</i>

1722
01:56:33,695 --> 01:56:38,240
<i>♪ It can never bring</i>
<i>the thing that used to be</i>

1723
01:56:38,408 --> 01:56:43,745
<i>♪ For I must have you or no one</i>

1724
01:56:43,913 --> 01:56:48,250
<i>♪ And so I'm through with love</i>

1725
01:56:49,085 --> 01:56:55,757
<i>♪ And... so I'm through... with...</i>

1726
01:56:55,925 --> 01:57:01,221
<i>♪ Baby, I'm through with love ♪</i>

1727
01:57:01,389 --> 01:57:04,516
[band continues playing]

1728
01:57:24,954 --> 01:57:26,455
Josephine.

1729
01:57:27,957 --> 01:57:30,751
Bienstock!

1730
01:57:31,586 --> 01:57:33,462
- [music stops]
- Hey. That's no dame.

1731
01:57:33,629 --> 01:57:35,964
[as Joe] None of that, Sugar.

1732
01:57:36,132 --> 01:57:38,175
No guy is worth it.

1733
01:57:38,468 --> 01:57:39,801
[running]

1734
01:57:41,512 --> 01:57:43,180
- Grab her.
- [screams]

1735
01:57:46,976 --> 01:57:49,269
Josephine?

1736
01:57:54,650 --> 01:57:56,443
It's all set.
Osgood's meeting us at the pier.

1737
01:57:56,611 --> 01:57:58,528
- We're not on the pier yet.
- Ah!

1738
01:57:59,781 --> 01:58:01,615
[women scream]

1739
01:58:26,974 --> 01:58:28,517
[woman shrieks]

1740
01:58:48,913 --> 01:58:50,330
Hi.

1741
01:58:50,540 --> 01:58:52,499
My friend Josephine,
gonna be a bridesmaid.

1742
01:58:52,667 --> 01:58:54,584
- Well, pleased to meet you.
- Come on.

1743
01:58:55,294 --> 01:58:57,045
She's so eager.

1744
01:59:04,095 --> 01:59:05,470
[bicycle horn]

1745
01:59:11,269 --> 01:59:13,854
Wait! Wait for Sugar!

1746
01:59:18,442 --> 01:59:20,777
- Another bridesmaid?
- Flower girl.

1747
01:59:20,945 --> 01:59:24,239
- Sugar, what are you doing?
- I told you, I'm not very bright.

1748
01:59:24,407 --> 01:59:25,824
Let's go.

1749
01:59:29,579 --> 01:59:31,121
You don't want me, Sugar.

1750
01:59:31,289 --> 01:59:33,748
I'm a liar and a phony.
A saxophone player.

1751
01:59:33,916 --> 01:59:36,126
One of those no-goodniks
you keep running away from.

1752
01:59:36,294 --> 01:59:37,752
I know. Every time.

1753
01:59:37,920 --> 01:59:41,256
Sugar, do yourself a favor.
Go back to the millionaires.

1754
01:59:41,424 --> 01:59:42,757
The sweet end of the lollipop,

1755
01:59:42,925 --> 01:59:44,801
not the coleslaw in the face,
the old socks

1756
01:59:44,969 --> 01:59:46,761
and the squeezed-out tube of toothpaste.

1757
01:59:46,929 --> 01:59:50,015
That's right, pour it on.
Talk me out of it.

1758
01:59:54,854 --> 01:59:57,439
I called Mama.
She was so happy, she cried.

1759
01:59:57,607 --> 02:00:00,442
She wants you to have
her wedding gown. It's white lace.

1760
02:00:00,610 --> 02:00:03,945
Osgood, I can't get married in your
mother's dress. [nervous chuckle]

1761
02:00:04,113 --> 02:00:08,200
[stammers] She and I,
we are not built the same way.

1762
02:00:08,367 --> 02:00:11,119
- We can have it altered.
- Oh no, you don't.

1763
02:00:12,455 --> 02:00:15,707
Osgood, I'm gonna level with you.
We can't get married at all.

1764
02:00:15,875 --> 02:00:17,125
Why not?

1765
02:00:17,293 --> 02:00:18,543
Well...

1766
02:00:18,711 --> 02:00:21,338
In the first place,
I'm not a natural blonde.

1767
02:00:21,505 --> 02:00:22,881
Doesn't matter.

1768
02:00:23,507 --> 02:00:25,467
I smoke. I smoke all the time.

1769
02:00:25,635 --> 02:00:26,968
I don't care.

1770
02:00:27,595 --> 02:00:28,553
I have a terrible past.

1771
02:00:28,721 --> 02:00:31,473
For three years I've been
living with a saxophone player.

1772
02:00:31,641 --> 02:00:33,141
I forgive you.

1773
02:00:35,394 --> 02:00:37,979
I can never have children.

1774
02:00:38,147 --> 02:00:42,400
- We can adopt some.
- You don't understand, Osgood.

1775
02:00:42,568 --> 02:00:43,818
<i>Aw...</i>

1776
02:00:43,986 --> 02:00:47,864
- I'm a man.
- Well, nobody's perfect.

